 {{flagicon|Antigua and Barbuda}} [[V. C. Bird International Airport|Antigua]]\n| 10,825\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 27\n| {{flagicon|Cura\u00e7ao}} [[Cura\u00e7ao International Airport|Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| 10,263\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 28\n| {{flagicon|United States}} [[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]]\n| 8,877\n| [[American Airlines]]\n|-\n| 29\n| {{flagicon|United States}} [[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]]\n| 6,695\n| [[American Airlines]]\n|-\n| 30\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Montr\u00e9al-Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al-Trudeau]]\n| 6,215\n| [[Air Transat]]\n|-\n| 31\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Malpensa Airport|Milan-Malpensa]]\n| 6,130\n| [[Blue Panorama Airlines]]\n|-\n| 32\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Toronto Pearson International Airport|Toronto-Pearson]]\n| 6,031\n| [[Air Transat]]\n|-\n| 33\n| {{flagicon|Aruba}} [[Queen Beatrix International Airport|Aruba]]\n| 5,176\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 34\n| {{flagicon|Dominica}} [[Douglas-Charles Airport|Dominica]]\n| 4,924\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 35\n| {{flagicon|Anguilla}} [[Clayton J. Lloyd International Airport|Anguilla]]\n| 4,376\n| [[Air Santo Domingo]], [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 36\n| {{flagicon|Jamaica}} [[Norman Manley International Airport|Kingston]]\n| 3,338\n| [[InterCaribbean Airways]], [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 37\n| {{flagicon|United States}} [[Dallas Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas-Fort Worth]]\n| 3,179\n| [[American Airlines]]\n|-\n| 38\n| {{flagicon|Saint Kitts and Nevis}} [[Robert L. Bradshaw International Airport|St. Kitts]]\n| 2,231\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 39\n| {{flagicon|Bonaire}} [[Flamingo International Airport|Bonaire]]\n| 2,109\n| [[Sky High Aviation Services|Sky High]]\n|-\n| 40\n| {{flagicon|Venezuela}} [[Jacinto Lara International Airport|Barquisimeto]]\n| 1,792\n| [[Venezolana]]\n|}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On February 15, 1970, a [[Dominicana de Aviaci\u00f3n]] [[DC-9]] flying to [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn International Airport]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], crashed, killing all 102 people on board (see: [[Dominicana DC-9 air disaster]]).\n* On 30 January 1975, [[Douglas DC-3]] HI-222 of [[L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas Nacionales S. A. (Peru)|LANSA]] crashed on take-off, killing one of the 30 people on board. The aircraft was on an international scheduled passenger flight to [[Mais Gate Airport]], [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]].<ref name=ASN300175>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19750130-1 |title=HI-222 Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of the busiest airports in Dominican Republic]]\n* [[List of the busiest airports in the Caribbean]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline|Las Am\u00e9ricas International Airport}}\n* [http://www.aerodom.com/app/do/lasamericas.aspx Aeropuerto Internacional Las Am\u00e9ricas-JFPG]\n* {{WAD|MDSD}}\n\n{{portalbar|Dominican Republic|Aviation}}\n{{Airports in the Dominican Republic}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Las Americas International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Santo Domingo Province]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1959]]\n[[Category:1959 establishments in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Cumbripie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCargo:FedEx", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Las_Am%C3%A9ricas_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Imperia Online JSC", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Imperia Online JSC\n| logo = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2009\n| location_city = [[Sofia]]\n| location_country = [[Bulgaria]]\n| key_people = Moni Dochev<br />Dobroslav Dimitrov\n| num_employees = 70+\n| industry = [[Mobile games]], [[video game development]], [[multiplayer video game]]s, [[social network game]]s, [[browser game]]s\n| homepage = {{URL|www.imperiaonline.bg}}\n}}\n\n'''Imperia Online JSC''' is a Bulgarian game production and publishing company founded by Moni Dochev and Dobroslav Dimitrov.<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Official History of IO|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/from-hobby-to-professional-game-studio/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=facts>{{cite web|title=Impeia Online's History in a Few Facts|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/our-history-in-a-few-facts/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Based in [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]], the company originally concentrated primarily on browser-based games with their main title being ''[[Imperia Online]]'', but later started developing mobile games as well.<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|title=Timeline of IO's games|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/timeline/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg}}</ref><ref name=launchub>{{cite news|title=Imperia Online and the Global Invasion of The Great People|url=http://launchub.com/imperia-online-and-the-global-invasion-of-the-great-people/|accessdate=13 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120175920/http://launchub.com/imperia-online-and-the-global-invasion-of-the-great-people/|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 21, 2018, Imperia Online has become part of Stillfront Group, a group of independent creators, publishers, and distributors of digital games. Stillfront operates through eleven near-autonomous subsidiaries: Imperia Online in Bulgaria, {{ill|Bytro Labs|de}}, OFM Studios, [[Goodgame Studios]] and {{ill|Playa Games|de}} in Germany, {{ill|Coldwood Interactive|sv}} in Sweden, [[Power Challenge]] in the UK and Sweden, Dorado Online Games in Malta, [[Simutronics]] in the United States, Babil Games in UAE and Jordan, and [[eRepublik]] in Ireland and Romania. Stillfront\u2019s games are distributed globally. The main markets are Germany, the United States, France, UK and MENA.<ref name=\"Stillfront Group\">{{cite news|title=Stillfront Group completes the acquisition of Imperia Online JSC|url=https://www.stillfront.com/stillfront-group-ab-stillfront-group-completes-the-acquisition-of-imperia-online-jsc-2//|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019 the company has more 25 games in its portfolio, and has several more in development. Imperia Online JSC now develops games for web browsers, [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]] and social networks like [[Facebook]], [[Odnoklassniki]] and [[VK (social networking)|Vkontakte.]]<ref name=reddit>{{cite web|title=Imperia Online Co-Founder Dobroslav Dimitrov - reddit AMA|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/2ne2ny/i_am_dobroslav_dimitrov_cofounder_and_lead_game/|website=reddit.com|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nImperia Online JSC was officially founded in September 2009, but the idea for it was born along with its main product - the [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] Imperia Online in 2005. Detailed research and crafting of the gameplay, mechanics and programming for the company's main product were done by the game\u2019 and company's founders Dobroslav Dimitrov - Gameplay Designer, and Moni Dochev - Freelance Developer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview with Imperia Online: How to Build a Game for 25 Million Users?|url=http://80.lv/articles/interview-with-imperia-online-how-to-build-a-game-for-25-million-users/|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2005 an idea grows into a concept and on August 23 Era 1 of Realm 1 of Imperia Online goes live and the story begins.\n\nIn 2006 realms of 2 brand new upgraded Imperia Online's versions are officially live. The game is translated into 12 languages thanks to the freelance Community managers and translators the company assigned. In the same year the first of its kind Imperia Online tournament is held - Nomads Invasions.\n\nIn 2007 Imperia Online JSC launched Galactic Imperia - a new web-based project with Modern Military context.\n\nAlmost a whole year of conceptualizing complicated game mechanics leads to the final publication of Global Wars in March 2008.\n\nIn 2009, Imperia Online JSC launched its first [[role-playing game]] - [[Imperial Hero]]. The [[Role-playing game|RPG]] was published after a year of conceptual and technical development. Again in 2009 Ludo was launched for [[iOS]] and [[Facebook]] - the classic turn-based board game now can be played with thousands of real players online.\n\nThe next year - in 2010 - Imperia Online JSC launched Online Artillery - a turn-based cannon shooter.\n\nIn 2011 Imperia Online's World Cup tournament was held for the first time with the Bulgarian national team winning the first place.\n\nIn 2012 the second World Cup was held, won again by the Bulgarians. The medieval strategy got its official appearance in the Apple App Store. The same year Imperia Online JSC was among the exhibitors at On!Fest.\n\nIn 2013 the third Imperia Online tournament was conducted and this time it was won by the Croatians. By that time there were already more than 100 people working in the company and the first of its kind school for game developers \u2013 Imperial Training Camp - was opened. Throughout the year Imperia Online kept spreading by getting released on [[iOS]] and in the largest Russian social network [[Odnoklassniki]]. It also became available for Android users. Later that year the newest - and current - version of Imperia Online is launched - Version 6, called \u2018The Great People\u2019 with brand new graphic design, enriched and diversified gameplay. Imperia Online JSC was among the exhibitors at [[Gamescom]], Dubai World Game Expo and On!Fest. In the same year the company sponsored Sofia Game Jam, Intergame, Tallinn and the #archHackaton and also the Bulgarian Boogie Woogie Dance team for the World Championship in Moscow, Russia.\n\nIn 2014 \u2018IO: The Great People\u2019 is also launched for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Windows Phone]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/bg-bg/p/imperia-online/9wzdncrdjzxw?rtc=1&activetab=pivot:overviewtab|title=Imperia Online in Windows store|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Facebook]]. [[Microsoft]] chose Imperia Online for its \u2018Featured\u2019 section in [[Windows Store]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.imperiaonline.bg/bg/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/10728735_10201851371125846_133683349_n.jpg|title=Imperia Online n 'Featured' in Windows Store|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the second half of the year Imperia Online JSC launched several mobile games, starting with Mad Moles and Online Artillery 2 in August - both of them for [[iOS]] and [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/online-artillery-now-conquering-facebook/|title=Online Artillery Now Conquering Facebook|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Later that year Mad Moles received an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version as well. In October 2014 Rocket Chameleon was released for [[iOS]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/rocket-chameleon-available-on-%d1%82he-app-store/|title=Rocket Chameleon Available on The App Store|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and later got an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/rocket-chameleon-successfully-landed-on-google-play/|title=Rocket Chameleon Successfully Landed on Google Play|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In November 2014 Imperia Online JSC released Egg Tales for [[iOS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/start-your-eggciting-adventure-with-egg-tales/|title=Start Your Eggciting Adventure With Egg Tales!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> - a casual game that follows the adventures of an egg that tumbled out of the safety of its nest and landed deep in a terrifying cave. The arcade jumper quickly rose to the top of the Bulgarian App Store in the \u2018Free\u2019 category. In the meantime - from mid-October until the end of November 2014 the fourth Imperia Online World Cup was held, this time won by Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/brazil-is-the-new-world-champion-of-imperia-online/|title=Brazil Is The New World Champion Of Imperia Online!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Imperia Online JSC sponsored the Black Sea Solo Kayak Expedition, HackFMI and is also one of the sponsors of Launchub.<ref name=\"launchub\" /> That year Imperia Online JSC was among the exhibitors at [[Gamescom]] and at Intergame Tallinn where Dobroslav Dimitrov took part in it as a speaker, giving a talk on 'Winning the War for Software Engineering Talent'. Imperia Online JSC is a member of BAIT (Bulgarian Association of Information Technologies) and BASSCOM (Bulgarian Association of Software Technologies).\n\nIn 2015 Imperia Online JSC released a number of titles including the RPG Imperial Hero II - a remake of Imperial Hero, launched for Android, Facebook and web. Meanwhile, Imperia Online for Windows Phone was published by Game Troopers and became a featured mobile Xbox title by Microsoft. In January 2015 Imperia Online JSC released the medieval turn-based strategy [[Seasons of War (Mobile Strategy Game)|Seasons of War]] for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/seasons-of-war-now-available-on-google-play/|title=\u2018Seasons of War\u2019 Now Available On Google Play|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and later for iOS too. The same month Jolly Join and Golem Wars are launched for iOS. The following month Robo Risk and Cluster Six are launched for iOS and EggTales is launched for Android. In June Imperia Online JSC released Ishi for Android. Two months after that the company was among the exhibitors at Gamescom. In October Imperia Online JSC released FlapOTron 3D for iOS and Ludo Blitz, the upgraded version of Ludo from 2009, for iOS, Android and Facebook. The same month the company's COO, Cvetan Rusimov visited Game Connection Paris, where he was a speaker at the conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/game-connection-2015/|title=Imperia Online goes to Game Connection 2015!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The following month Online Artillery 2.0 is launched for Android and released in a 3D Touch Edition for iPhone 6s. In December 2015 Ishi GO is launched for iOS. At the end of the year Imperia Online JSC stepped into partnership with VKontakte and Imperia Online for Android and iOS was integrated into the game section of VK's platform.\n\n2016 started with the team exhibiting at Casual Connect Amsterdam, having an Indie nomination for Online Artillery 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515145420/http://indieprize.org/europe/|title=Indie nomination for Online Artillery 2|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In April Imperia Online was launched on [[Steam (software)|Steam]]. That same month Dobroslav Dimitrov, Imperia Online's Co-Founder, took part in Webit 2016 in a panel discussion entitled \u2018Introduction to Endeavor and lessons learned from leveraging global, local or no capital\u2019. In May Imperia Online JSC released the game Viber Emperors for Android and [[iOS]]. The game got translated to 30 languages, featured modules like \u2018Ask a Viber Friend\u2019 and had its own custom sticker package. Moni Dochev, the other Co-Founder participated in the jury of the E-volution Awards by Forbes that month. Again in May Ludo Blitz is released in [[Windows Store]]. During the summer Cvetan Rusimov, the COO of Imperia Online JSC, took part as a speaker in the conferences Pocket Gamer Connects in Helsinki<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-at-pocket-gamer-connects/|title=Imperia Online at Pocket Gamer Connects|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and Vancouver,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/cvetan-rusimov-as-speaker-at-pocket-gamer-connects/|title=Cvetan Rusimov as speaker at Pocket Gamer Connects|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mobile Game Asia and Israel Mobile Summit 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-is-all-over-the-world/|title=Imperia Online is All Over the World|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Apart from that the company attended Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles, USA. In November Cvetan Rusimov, was a speaker at Game Connection Paris for a second consecutive year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-at-game-connection-paris/|title=Imperia Online at Game Connection, Paris|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> From the end of October 2016 until mid-December the fifth Imperia Online World cup was held and it was won by Poland.\n\nIn the beginning of 2017, in January, Cvetan Rusimov attended the International Mobile Gaming Awards (IMGA) in China where he was a member of the jury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-between-china-and-uk/|title=Imperia Online between China and UK|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Immediately after that he attended the Mobile Games Forum in UK where he was a speaker. The next month the COO of the company, took part in the 4th GameFounders international investment program as one of the three mentors at Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. Also that month Imperia Online was the first web-based game to integrate ClanPlay - a social app for better communication for players to use in-game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/venture-beat-imperia-online-one-of-the-first-to-integrate-clanplay/|title=Venture Beat: Imperia Online \u2013 one of the first to integrate ClanPlay|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Meanwhile, the team attended Casual Connect in Berlin. In March Imperia Online JSC stepped into partnership with Play 3arabi - a mobile game publisher focused on the MENA region - releasing Kingdoms Online which is an adapted mobile version of Imperia Online for the Arabic-speaking players in the MENA region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-in-partnership-with-play-3arabi/|title=Imperia Online in Partnership with Play 3arabi|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The same month the company's COO, Cvetan Rusimov was one of the speakers at Global Mobile Game Confederation (GMGC) in Beijing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-to-be-present-at-gmgc-and-dgc-games-conferences/|title=Imperia Online to be Present at GMGC and DGC Games Conferences|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He attended another conference later that month called Digital Games Conference (DGC) in Dubai - where he held another lecture.<ref name=\":0\" /> At the end of March 2017 Imperia Online JSC, partnered with Huawei Company released their game Imperia Online on HiGame - Huawei's android mobile game platform. In April, Cvetan Rusimov was a speaker at Reboot Develop 2017. The COO, Cvetan Rusimov hit another speaking stage at Game Access in Czech Republic. The COO also joined Casual Connect Asia. Meanwhile, the studio became part of the 25 most valuable companies income-wise in Bulgaria's IT industry according to Capital Magazine's case study. Mariela Tzvetanova, CMO at Imperia Online, was one of the key speakers of Israel Mobile Summit, presenting the lecture Beauty and the Beast of Brand Diversification. At the end of June 2017, Cvetan Rusimov, was back on the stage during Pocket Gamer Connects in San Francisco with the session \u201cWhy US games can\u2019t copy their own success in China - and how to fix this\u201d. Meanwhile, Mariela Tzvetanova attended Game Development Summit (GDS) and presented: Beauty and the Beast of Brand Diversification. The MMO Game of Emperors was launched on Steam. Later on, in August, the COO, Cvetan Rusimov was a lector at Game Scope and a keynote speaker at Devcom in Cologne - where he held another lecture. In the beginning of September Cvetan Rusimov was a speaker at Dev.Play Conference. During that time the CMO, Mariela Tzvetanova was one of the speakers of Pocket Gamer Connects in Helsinki, presenting \"\u0422op 10 Tips \u2013 How To Work With MENA Influencers\". In October, as a premium partner of Huawei Mobile, the company was invited to the official announcement of HiApp Europe in Berlin. Right after, both Cvetan Rusimov and Mariela Tzvetanova gave separate talks at Game Connection in Paris. At the end of the year the studio's COO Cvetan Rusimov was a jury for a second time at IMGA China. At the end of 2017 Game of Emperors was launched on Windows.\n\nIn January, 2018 Cvetan Rusimov was part of the Prize Judges of Indie Prize at Casual Connect America. The same month the CMO, Mariela Tzvetanova, gave a talk on: 'Social Media Manager vs. Community Manager: What's the Difference?' at Pocket Gamer Connects in London. Later on in February 2018, the CEO, Dobroslav Dimitrov and COO, Cvetan Rusimov attended Mobile Games Forum in London. In March, both CEO and COO, represented the company at GDC and Game Connection in San Francisco. During the next month the CMO, Mariela Tzvetanova and Senior Marketing & BizDev Manager, Anya Shopova attended SheLeader which was held in Sofia. At the end of the month Digital Games Conference in Dubai was attended by the COO, Cvetan Rusimov. In May 2018 Cvetan Rusimov was a speaker at Nordic Game conference. And right after, together with the Marketing & BizDev Team, attended Casual Connect in London, where Game of Emperors was nominated for Indie Prize. At that time Imperia Online is already available on Samsung Galaxy App Store and MI App Store India. In June 2018, the CEO, Dobroslav Dimitrov, was announced as the chairman of BASSCOM. In August the company was present at Gamescom with its C-level and Marketing & BizDev Team. It the end of September the CEO, Dobroslav Dimitrov, was a speaker of Game Dev Summit held in Sofia. Meanwhile the COO, Cvetan Rusimov, was a speaker at Mobile Growth Summit. In October the Marketing & BizDev Team attended Casual Connect in Serbia where Kingdoms Online was nominated for Indie Prize and our COO was among the speakers at the conference. Meanwhile the company launched its new publishing program for games. During the same month Imperia Online JSC participated in Sofia Games Night, right before Dev.Play Conference, where Cvetan Rusimov was a speaker for a second year in a row. A week later, the company\u2019s COO attended White Nights Conference in Moscow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-will-be-part-of-sofia-game-night/|title=Imperia Online will be part of Sofia Game Night|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> And after that was also a speaker at Game Connection in Paris where together with the Marketing and BizDev Manager, Mario Vasilev, represented the company with a booth together with [[Telus International]]. In October, the COO, Cvetan Rusimov, participated at Huawei Eco-Connect in Rome, Italy. Meanwhile at the end of the same month until middle of December, the 8th edition of World Cup was hosted, later won by the USA team. Right before the end of the year, Imperia Online was already available on KakaoTalk and One Store for Korea.\n\nIn January 2019, the company COO, Cvetan Rusimov, and Marketing and BizDev Manager, Mario Vasilev, attended PGC in London. During the event Mario Vasilev participated in the panel \u201cManaging Your Community Across Platforms\u201d.\n\nCvetan Rusimov was part of Quo Vadis, Berlin in April 2019. The same month Mario Vasilev was a speaker at GDD in Tallinn.\n\nImperia Online visited the Webit.Festival Europe 2019 from May 13th to May 15th in NDK, Sofia. Imperia Online JSC was among the exhibitors at Nordic Game expo 2019, Malmo.\n\nThe studio heads and biz dev team visited Gamescom. Again in Germany Cvetan Rusimov gave a M&A Masterclass at Baltic Dev Days on September 12, 2019.\n\nImperia Online\u2019s tournament \u2013 the World Cup 2019 \u2013 opened on September 25. At the beginning of December was announced the winner - Romania. \n\nImperia Online attended\u00a0 Pocket Gamer Connects which was held in Helsinki between October 1-2, 2019. Mario Vasilev was a speaker. Mariela Tzvetanova, the CMO, talked about \u201cTop 10 tips on how to work with MENA Influencers\u201d at Game Connection, Paris 2019 edition. Cvetan Rusimov gave the M&A Masterclass at DevGAMM Minsk 2019 on November 21st.\n\n== Figures ==\n* As of January 2018 Imperia Online JSC, has more than 40 million registered users in its main product - Imperia Online.\n* The company and its games have nearly 650,000 fans across their [[Facebook]] pages.\n* The annual revenue of Imperia Online JSC for 2017 is 5,3 Million Euro.\n* The revenue for the period 2012-2017 is 33,2 Million Euro. And since 2018 Imperia Online is officially part of Stillfront Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-is-now-part-of-stillfront-group/|title=Imperia Online is now part of Stillfront Group|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* The game production company currently resides on 1,200 square meters of office space in Bulgaria's most luxurious office building - [http://www.buildingoftheyear.bg/en/buildings/view/299/Infinity-Tower.html Infinity Tower].<ref name=mdm>{{cite web|title=National Contest BUILDING OF THE YEAR |url=http://www.buildingoftheyear.bg/en/buildings/view/299/Infinity-Tower.html|accessdate=13 January 2015|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n* As of January 2018 Imperia Online JSC has more than 70 employees.\n* Imperia Online JSC and its products are popular in more than 194 countries.\n\n== Games ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Platform(s) !! Genre !! Description \n|-\n| [[Imperia Online]]|| 2005|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows Phone]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]]|| Strategy game set in the Medieval Era where the player develops his empire by building, research and battles.\n|-\n| Galactic Imperia|| 2007|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] || The player takes control of a commander of a planet full of resources which have to be used to build an armada of spaceships and to destroy the opposition.\n|-\n| Global Wars|| 2008|| [[Browser game|Browser]]||[[MMORTS]]|| A simulated parallel universe, where you have the modern economic, political and warfare systems and technologies to develop your state and counquer others.\n|-\n| [[Imperial Hero]]|| 2009|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]] || A cross-platform game, leading to the wondrous and amazing lands of Ayarr Empire, which await all eminent heroes who wish to achieve glory, immortality and become legends.\n|-\n| Ludo|| 2009|| [[iOS]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| Turn-based Board Game || A turn-based board game for 2-4 people, one of the most played family games in the world. Family game.\n|-\n| Online Artillery|| 2010|| [[iOS]]|| Turn-based cannon shooter || A remake of the classic 8-Bit Artillery game.\n|-\n| Mad Moles|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| [[Arcade game]] || Based on the classic whack-a-mole concept but with a twist.\n|-\n| Online Artillery 2|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| Turn-based cannon shooter || The upgraded version of IO's Online Artillery from 2010.\n|-\n| Rocket Chameleon|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Arcade game]] || An entertaining mixture of color matching and endless runner.\n|-\n| Egg Tales|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Platform game|Jumper]] || A casual game that follows the adventures of an egg that tumbled out of the safety of its nest and landed deep in a terrifying cave.\n|-\n| Ishi||2015 ||[[Android (operating system)|Android]] ||[[Arcade game]] || An arcade game where the player takes control over a stone creature called Ishi and have to navigate their way around deep dark caves while collecting gems and defeating nasty baddies.\n|-\n| Seasons of War|| 2015|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Turn-based strategy|TBS]] || Allows the player to become the Governor of a distant Imperial city and grow their holding through wise rule.\n|-\n| Ludo Blitz ||2015 ||[[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Facebook]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows store]], [[Browser game|Browser]] ||Turn-based Board Game || This game is the upgraded version of IO's Ludo from 2009.\n|-\n| Golem Wars||2015||[[iOS]] ||[[Turn-based strategy|TBS]] || Turn-based strategy game that allows the player to become the Master of a golem army.\n|-\n| Jolly Join ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||Puzzle game || A charming color matching puzzler with simple rules.\n|-\n| Cluster Six ||2015 ||[[iOS]], [[Apple TV]] ||[[Side-scrolling video game|Side-scroller game]] || Side-scroller game that sends the player to a feature.\n|-\n| Robo Risk ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||Climbing simulator || Sci-Fi climbing simulator with random level generation and endless gameplay.\n|-\n| YoHoHo ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||[[Arcade game]] || Keep captain Flyn afloat and out of the water as he sails across the sea.\n|-\n| FlapOTron ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||[[Arcade game]] || The players have to avoid touching the towers using 3D Touch to control the Electron.\n|-\n| Ishi GO ||2015 ||iOS ||[[Arcade game]] || Another addictive game where the players have to dodge through the rocks using 3D Touch control.\n|-\n| Imperial Hero II ||2015||[[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Facebook]] ||[[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]] || The upgraded version of Imperia Online's Imperial hero from 2009.\n|-\n| Game of Emperors ||2016||[[Browser game|Browser]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[Facebook]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows Store]]||[[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] || The players develop their own cities by constructing economic and military buildings, researching in the University in the Capital and expanding their army, which will fight in the battles.\n|-\n| MedCorps || 2016 || [[iOS]] || Strategy, Simulation || The player has to control a team of specialists, fight diseases, grow his organization and ultimately save the world from dangerous viruses.\n|-\n|Kingdoms Online\n|2017\n|[[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n|[[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]]\n|Adapted mobile version of Imperia Online for the Arabic-speaking players in the MENA region.\n|}\n\n== Training and education ==\nIn 2013 Imperia Online JSC established the first tuition-free school for game developers in Bulgaria. It was originally named Imperial Training Camp and its first season prepared 40 enthusiasts for the professional [[PHP]]/[[MySQL]] and [[Java (programming language)|Java]]/[[Android (operating system)|Android]] fields. 20 of those 40 graduates were hired by Imperia Online JSC, and the rest were recommended to other software companies.\n\nIn 2014 the second season of IO's Training Camp drew even higher interest and this time there were 80 students, divided into 4 groups of 20: 62 graduated, of which 30 were hired by Imperia Online JSC.\n\nFor the third season Imperia Online JSC was joined by another Bulgarian company - Trader.bg - and the school was renamed to \u201cIT Talents Training Camp\u201d. By that time the courses are [[PHP]]/ [[MySQL]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]]/ [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[JavaScript]], [[Objective-C]]/[[iOS]], and [[Java SE]] / [[Java EE]].  In January 2015 the third season ended with a big part of the 115 participants getting hired.\n\nEvery year, there are 180 cadets successfully graduated from the academy. IT Talents Training Camp is already partnering with over 80 companies in the IT industry, to provide them qualified IT specialists. The initiative registers more than 2000 applications per season, from which around 200 most motivated candidates are allowed to enter the intensive 5-month courses. IT Talents is an NGO since 2016 and is provided with Google Ad Grants, enabling free AdWords campaigns. As of November 2017, The Municipality of Burgas organizes a 5-month program in cooperation with IT Talents. The training is again completely free and the applications are done by filling in a short registration form.\n\n== Outsourcing ==\nIn May 2015 Imperia Online JSC founded a private company for IT outsourcing called Imperia Mobile Ltd. Till the end of the year the new unit led by Radoslav Gaydarski had already successfully released more than 10 major projects. The outsourcing company offers a full range of services to execute a technical project and overcome any challenges, relying on the full capacity of over 165 professional developers, designers, artists, QA specialists and business developers. In January 2017 Imperia Mobile Ltd. started a rebranding process to the new name of Upnetix, which was completed in April 2017. The company has over 50 released projects and know-how in more than 10 industries. In September 2018, the company was acquired by one of the leading IT companies in Bulgaria - ScaleFocus.\n\n\n== Awards and Nominations ==\nImperia Online JSC was awarded in the \u2018Corporate and Social Responsibility\u2019 Category and nominated for the \u2018Education\u2019 Category of BAIT's 2014 Awards.\n\nImperia Online JSC was proclaimed \u2018A Rising Star\u2019 in [[Deloitte]]\u2019s Fastest Growing IT companies ranking for 2014 with a growth of 498%.\n\nImperia Online JSC was nominated in three categories of the 2014 Game Connection Awards:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-competing-for-three-awards-in-paris/|title=Imperia Online Competing For Three Awards in Paris|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* \u2018Promising IP\u2019\n* \u2018Desktop Downloadable\u2019\n* \u2018Hardcore Game\u2019\n\nIn February 2019, Imperia Online received from the President of Republic of Bulgaria Rumen Radev a mark of \u201cExcellence in Innovation\u201d.\n\nImperia Online JSC was nominated for \u2018App Developer of 2014\u2019 at The Appsters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-running-for-app-developer-2014/|title=Imperia Online Running for App Developer of 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Imperia Online JSC was awarded by [[Deloitte]] as the 14th fastest growing IT company in Central Europe, having 592% revenue growth from 2011 to 2014. Again in 2015 Imperia Online JSC was nominated in three categories for \u2018Forbes Business Awards 2015\u2019:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/bg/Documents/technology-media-telecommunications/ce_tf_50_2015.pdf|title=Technology Fast 50 Powerful Connections 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Employee of the Year\n* Business Development\n* Human Resources Development\n\nImperia Online JSC employee, Ilian Iliev, was awarded 2nd place as Employee of the Year, by Forbes Bulgaria Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-employee-rewarded-by-forbes-bulgaria-magazine/|title=Imperia Online Employee Rewarded by Forbes Bulgaria Magazine!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 both albums with the music of Imperia Online has been featured in \u2018Amazon Hot New Releases\u2019 in Soundtrack (best-selling new and future releases). The music, by the composer Hristo Hristov, climbs to Top 10 in Amazon.de Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/imperia-online-soundtracks-are-breaking-the-charts/|title=Imperia Online Soundtracks are Breaking the Charts!|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, at Bulgarian Game Awards Imperia Online JSC is nominated for \u2019Best Workplace\u2019 and \u2018Developer of the year\u2019 while two of its titles are nominated in the following categories:\n\n* Imperial Hero II - for Best visual style/art, Best world, Best Mobile Game\n* Seasons of War - for Game of the year\n\nIn September 2016 Two titles of Imperia Online JSC are nominated at TIGA Games Industry Awards 2016  in the following categories:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/the-2016-tiga-games-industry-awards-finalists-revealed|title=TIGA Game Industry Awards 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Imperial Hero II - for Best Strategy and Best Role Playing\n* Imperia Online - for Game of the Year\n\nIn January 2017 Imperia Online JSC was nominated as a National Champion in the Customer Focus category at 'Europ\u0435an Business Awards'.\n\nThe same month Imperia Online JSC was nominated at Forbes Business Awards for the category: Customer relationship policy.\n\nImperia Online JSC was nominated at Bulgarian Association of Information Technologies (BAIT) awards  in the following categories:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bait-awards.bg/pages/Nominated/|title=BAIT Awards 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Corporate social responsibility\n* Entertainment software\n\nAt the end of January one of the company's games - Seasons of War got nominated for Indie Prize at Casual Connect in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indieprize.org/berlin2017/index.html#entry-105|title=Casual Connect Berlin 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn February Imperia Online's game Viber Emperors was nominated at the 13th International Mobile Game Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imgawards.com/news/13th-international-mobile-gaming-awards-global-nominees-announced/|title=IMGA 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn April Imperia Online's Kingdoms Online received a nomination for E-volution Awards by Forbes Bulgaria for the category \"Going Abroad\".\n\nThe same month Viber Emperors won the prize in \"Best Gaming App\" Category at the Webit Awards 2017 held in Sofia, Bulgaria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manager.bg/pr-i-sbitiya/webit-razdade-godishnite-si-nagradi|title=13-th Webit Awards 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nCompany's CEO, Dobroslav Dimitrov was \u0430 finalist at the 10th edition of \u201cManager of the Year\u201d contest for Bulgaria organized by Manager Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mng.manager.bg/|title=Manager of the Year|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the flagship title of the company - Imperia Online was among the nominated games for favourite Strategy at TIGA Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tiga.org/awards/2017-winners|title=TIGA Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nA month later, Imperia Online JSC got a nomination at The Global Entrepreneurship Monitor (GEM) for the category Partnerships for the cooperation with Game Troopers on Windows platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gemorg.bg/gem-bulgaria-awards-2017/|title=The Global Entrepreneurship Monitor (GEM)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn December, Imperia Online JSC was announced as one of the finalists at the National contest \u201cInnovative Enterprise of the Year\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enterprise-europe-network.bg/bg/topic/news/?nid=18097|title=Innovative Enterprise of the Year|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2017, Imperia Online JSC won three awards at Forbes Business Awards in the following categories:\n\n* Business Development,\n* Client Policy,\n* Human Resources.\n\nImperia Online JSC was awarded in the \u2018Best Bulgarian ICT Product\u2019 Category of BAIT's 2017 Awards for the game Kingdoms Online - fully localized in Arabic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bait-awards.bg/News/Izvestni-sa-pobeditelite-v-konkursa-%E2%80%9ENagradite-na-BAIT%E2%80%9C-za-2017-g/53/|title=BAIT Awards 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 Imperia Online JSC was among the finalists at \u201cEurop\u0435an Business Awards\" \"One to Watch\" List for Bulgaria in International Expansion category. In March the company was announced as a National Winner for 2017-18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessawardseurope.com/vote/detail-new/31/22956|title=European Business Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Game of Emperors was nominated for Indie Prize at Casual Connect in London. And right after announced as a winner for the Applovin workshop in San Francisco. In October 2018 Kingdoms Online was among the nominated games for Indie Prize at Casual Connect in Belgrade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.applovin.com/applovin-casual-connect-indie-developer-prize-2018/|title=Applovin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nGame of Emperors received a nomination for being one of the best strategy games at TIGA 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tiga.org/awards/2018-winners|title=TIGA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nImperia Online JSC was rewarded for being devoted in the initiative and the help in development of [[TUES]] [bg] part of Technical University of Sofia.\n\nIn November 2018 Imperia Online JSC was nominated and awarded for \u201cHigh achievements in the innovations\u201d at the national competition \u201cInnovative Enterprise of the Year\u201d with the RPG - Imperial Hero.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{Official website|www.imperiaonline.bg}}\n\n[[Category:Browser-based game websites]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Bulgaria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Imperia Online JSC\n| logo = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2009\n| location_city = [[Sofia]]\n| location_country = [[Bulgaria]]\n| key_people = Moni Dochev<br />Dobroslav Dimitrov\n| num_employees = 70+\n| industry = [[Mobile games]], [[video game development]], [[multiplayer video game]]s, [[social network game]]s, [[browser game]]s\n| homepage = {{URL|www.imperiaonline.bg}}\n}}\n\n'''Imperia Online JSC''' is a Bulgarian game production and publishing company founded by Moni Dochev and Dobroslav Dimitrov.<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Official History of IO|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/from-hobby-to-professional-game-studio/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=facts>{{cite web|title=Impeia Online's History in a Few Facts|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/our-history-in-a-few-facts/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Based in [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]], the company originally concentrated primarily on browser-based games with their main title being ''[[Imperia Online]]'', but later started developing mobile games as well.<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|title=Timeline of IO's games|url=http://www.imperiaonline.bg/company/timeline/|website=www.imperiaonline.bg}}</ref><ref name=launchub>{{cite news|title=Imperia Online and the Global Invasion of The Great People|url=http://launchub.com/imperia-online-and-the-global-invasion-of-the-great-people/|accessdate=13 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120175920/http://launchub.com/imperia-online-and-the-global-invasion-of-the-great-people/|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 21, 2018, Imperia Online has become part of Stillfront Group, a group of independent creators, publishers, and distributors of digital games. Stillfront operates through eleven near-autonomous subsidiaries: Imperia Online in Bulgaria, {{ill|Bytro Labs|de}}, OFM Studios, [[Goodgame Studios]] and {{ill|Playa Games|de}} in Germany, {{ill|Coldwood Interactive|sv}} in Sweden, [[Power Challenge]] in the UK and Sweden, Dorado Online Games in Malta, [[Simutronics]] in the United States, Babil Games in UAE and Jordan, and [[eRepublik]] in Ireland and Romania. Stillfront\u2019s games are distributed globally. The main markets are Germany, the United States, France, UK and MENA.<ref name=\"Stillfront Group\">{{cite news|title=Stillfront Group completes the acquisition of Imperia Online JSC|url=https://www.stillfront.com/stillfront-group-ab-stillfront-group-completes-the-acquisition-of-imperia-online-jsc-2//|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019 the company has more 25 games in its portfolio, and has several more in development. Imperia Online JSC now develops games for web browsers, [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Windows Phone]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]] and social networks like [[Facebook]], [[Odnoklassniki]] and [[VK (social networking)|Vkontakte.]]<ref name=reddit>{{cite web|title=Imperia Online Co-Founder Dobroslav Dimitrov - reddit AMA|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/2ne2ny/i_am_dobroslav_dimitrov_cofounder_and_lead_game/|website=reddit.com|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nImperia Online JSC was officially founded in September 2009, but the idea for it was born along with its main product - the [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] Imperia Online in 2005. Detailed research and crafting of the gameplay, mechanics and programming for the company's main product were done by the game\u2019 and company's founders Dobroslav Dimitrov - Gameplay Designer, and Moni Dochev - Freelance Developer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview with Imperia Online: How to Build a Game for 25 Million Users?|url=http://80.lv/articles/interview-with-imperia-online-how-to-build-a-game-for-25-million-users/|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 23, Imperia Online goes live.\n\nIn 2006 realms of 2 brand new upgraded Imperia Online's versions are officially live. The game is translated into 12 languages thanks to the freelance Community managers and translators the company assigned. In the same year the first of its kind Imperia Online tournament is held - Nomads Invasions.\n\nIn 2007 Imperia Online JSC launched Galactic Imperia - a new web-based project with Modern Military context.\n\nAlmost a whole year of conceptualizing complicated game mechanics leads to the final publication of Global Wars in March 2008.\n\nIn 2009, Imperia Online JSC launched its first [[role-playing game]] - [[Imperial Hero]]. The [[Role-playing game|RPG]] was published after a year of conceptual and technical development. Again in 2009 Ludo was launched for [[iOS]] and [[Facebook]].\n\nIn 2010 - Imperia Online JSC launched Online Artillery - a turn-based cannon shooter.\n\nIn 2011 Imperia Online's World Cup tournament was held for the first time.\n\nIn 2012 Imperia Online was released to the Apple App Store.\n\nIn 2013 the third Imperia Online tournament was conducted and this time it was won by the Croatians. By that time there were already more than 100 people working in the company and the first of its kind school for game developers \u2013 Imperial Training Camp - was opened. Throughout the year Imperia Online kept spreading by getting released on [[iOS]] and in the largest Russian social network [[Odnoklassniki]]. It also became available for Android users. Later that year the newest - and current - version of Imperia Online is launched - Version 6, called \u2018The Great People\u2019 with brand new graphic design, enriched and diversified gameplay. Imperia Online JSC was among the exhibitors at [[Gamescom]], Dubai World Game Expo and On!Fest. In the same year the company sponsored Sofia Game Jam, Intergame, Tallinn and the #archHackaton and also the Bulgarian Boogie Woogie Dance team for the World Championship in Moscow, Russia.\n\nIn 2014 ''IO: The Great People'' is also launched for [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Windows Phone]],<ref name=\"windowsphone\">{{cite web|title=Imperia Online in Windows Store|url=http://www.windowsphone.com/en-us/store/app/imperia-online-free-medieval-strategy-game/4a7482e0-48e2-44f5-97fe-f29346198999|website=www.windowsphone.com|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> and [[Facebook]]. [[Microsoft]] chose Imperia Online for its \u2018Featured\u2019 section in [[Windows Store]].<ref name=\"featured\">{{cite web|title=Imperia Online in 'Featured' in Windows Store|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/bg/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/10728735_10201851371125846_133683349_n.jpg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> In the second half of the year Imperia Online JSC launched several mobile games, starting with ''Mad Moles'' and ''Online Artillery 2'' in August - both of them for [[iOS]] and [[Facebook]].<ref name=\"OAFacebook\">{{cite web|title=Online Artillery Now Conquering Facebook|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=305|website=blog.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Later that year ''Mad Moles'' received an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version as well. In October 2014 ''Rocket Chameleon'' was released for [[iOS]]<ref name=\"RCiOS\">{{cite web|title=Rocket Chameleon Available On The App Store|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=106|website=blog.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> and later got an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version as well.<ref name=\"RCAndroid\">{{cite web|title=Rocket Chameleon Successfully Landed on Google Play|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=288|website=blog.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> In November 2014 Imperia Online JSC released ''Egg Tales'' for [[iOS]],<ref name=\"EggTalesiOS\">{{cite web|title=Start Your Eggciting Adventure With Egg Tales!|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=160|website=blog.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>  The arcade game rose to the top of the Bulgarian App Store in the \u2018Free\u2019 category. In the meantime - from mid-October until the end of November 2014 the fourth Imperia Online World Cup was held, this time won by Brazil.<ref name=\"wc\">{{cite news|title=Brazil Is The New World Champion Of Imperia Online!|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=254|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn 2015 Imperia Online JSC released a number of titles including the RPG Imperial Hero II - a remake of Imperial Hero, launched for Android, Facebook and web. Meanwhile, Imperia Online for Windows Phone was published by Game Troopers and became a featured mobile Xbox title by Microsoft. In January 2015 Imperia Online JSC released the medieval turn-based strategy Seasons of War for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref name=\"Seasons\">{{cite web|title=\u2018Seasons of War\u2019 Now Available On Google Play|url=http://blog.imperiaonline.bg/en/?p=258|website=blog.imperiaonline.bg|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> and later for iOS too. The same month Jolly Join and Golem Wars are launched for iOS. The following month Robo Risk and Cluster Six are launched for iOS and EggTales is launched for Android. In June Imperia Online JSC released Ishi for Android. In October Imperia Online JSC released FlapOTron 3D for iOS and Ludo Blitz, the upgraded version of Ludo from 2009, for iOS, Android and Facebook. The following month Online Artillery 2.0 is launched for Android and released in a 3D Touch Edition for iPhone 6s. In December 2015 Ishi GO is launched for iOS. At the end of the year Imperia Online JSC stepped into partnership with VKontakte and Imperia Online for Android and iOS was integrated into the game section of VK's platform.\n\n2016 started with the team exhibiting at Casual Connect Amsterdam, having an Indie nomination for Online Artillery 2.<ref name=\"Casual Connect Amsterdam\">{{cite journal|title=Casual Connect Amsterdam 2016|url=http://indieprize.org/europe/#entry-0/|accessdate=18 February 2016|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515145420/http://indieprize.org/europe/#entry-0/|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April Imperia Online was launched on [[Steam (software)|Steam]]. In May Imperia Online JSC released the game Viber Emperors for Android and [[iOS]]. The game got translated to 30 languages, featured modules like \u2018Ask a Viber Friend\u2019 and had its own custom sticker package. In May Ludo Blitz is released in [[Windows Store]]. \n\nIn early 2017 Imperia Online was the first web-based game to integrate ClanPlay, a social app used by players for communication in-game.<ref name=\"ClanPlay\">{{cite journal|title=ClanPlay provides messaging platform for clan-based mobile games|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/02/17/clanplay-provides-clan-based-multiplayer-platform-for-mobile-games/|accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref>  \n\nAt the end of March 2017 Imperia Online JSC, partnered with Huawei Company released their game Imperia Online on HiGame - Huawei's android mobile game platform.\n\nThe studio became part of the 25 most valuable companies income-wise in Bulgaria's IT industry according to a case study in ''Capital Magazine''.{{cn|date=February 2020}} The MMO Game of Emperors was launched on Steam.\n\n== Figures ==\n* As of January 2018 Imperia Online JSC, has more than 40 million registered users in its main product - Imperia Online.\n* The company and its games have nearly 650,000 fans across their [[Facebook]] pages.\n* The annual revenue of Imperia Online JSC for 2017 is 5,3 Million Euro.\n* The revenue for the period 2012-2017 is 33,2 Million Euro. And since 2018 Imperia Online is officially part of Stillfront Group.\n* The game production company currently resides on 1,200 square meters of office space in Bulgaria's most luxurious office building - [http://www.buildingoftheyear.bg/en/buildings/view/299/Infinity-Tower.html Infinity Tower].<ref name=mdm>{{cite web|title=National Contest BUILDING OF THE YEAR |url=http://www.buildingoftheyear.bg/en/buildings/view/299/Infinity-Tower.html|accessdate=13 January 2015|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n* As of January 2018 Imperia Online JSC has more than 70 employees.\n* Imperia Online JSC and its products are popular in more than 194 countries.\n\n== Games ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Platform(s) !! Genre !! Description \n|-\n| [[Imperia Online]]|| 2005|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows Phone]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]]|| Strategy game set in the Medieval Era where the player develops his empire by building, research and battles.\n|-\n| Galactic Imperia|| 2007|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] || The player takes control of a commander of a planet full of resources which have to be used to build an armada of spaceships and to destroy the opposition.\n|-\n| Global Wars|| 2008|| [[Browser game|Browser]]||[[MMORTS]]|| A simulated parallel universe, where you have the modern economic, political and warfare systems and technologies to develop your state and counquer others.\n|-\n| [[Imperial Hero]]|| 2009|| [[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]] || A cross-platform game, leading to the wondrous and amazing lands of Ayarr Empire, which await all eminent heroes who wish to achieve glory, immortality and become legends.\n|-\n| Ludo|| 2009|| [[iOS]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| Turn-based Board Game || A turn-based board game for 2-4 people, one of the most played family games in the world. Family game.\n|-\n| Online Artillery|| 2010|| [[iOS]]|| Turn-based cannon shooter || A remake of the classic 8-Bit Artillery game.\n|-\n| Mad Moles|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| [[Arcade game]] || Based on the classic whack-a-mole concept but with a twist.\n|-\n| Online Artillery 2|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Browser game|Browser]]|| Turn-based cannon shooter || The upgraded version of IO's Online Artillery from 2010.\n|-\n| Rocket Chameleon|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Arcade game]] || An entertaining mixture of color matching and endless runner.\n|-\n| Egg Tales|| 2014|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Platform game|Jumper]] || A casual game that follows the adventures of an egg that tumbled out of the safety of its nest and landed deep in a terrifying cave.\n|-\n| Ishi||2015 ||[[Android (operating system)|Android]] ||[[Arcade game]] || An arcade game where the player takes control over a stone creature called Ishi and have to navigate their way around deep dark caves while collecting gems and defeating nasty baddies.\n|-\n| Seasons of War|| 2015|| [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]|| [[Turn-based strategy|TBS]] || Allows the player to become the Governor of a distant Imperial city and grow their holding through wise rule.\n|-\n| Ludo Blitz ||2015 ||[[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Facebook]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows store]], [[Browser game|Browser]] ||Turn-based Board Game || This game is the upgraded version of IO's Ludo from 2009.\n|-\n| Golem Wars||2015||[[iOS]] ||[[Turn-based strategy|TBS]] || Turn-based strategy game that allows the player to become the Master of a golem army.\n|-\n| Jolly Join ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||Puzzle game || A charming color matching puzzler with simple rules.\n|-\n| Cluster Six ||2015 ||[[iOS]], [[Apple TV]] ||[[Side-scrolling video game|Side-scroller game]] || Side-scroller game that sends the player to a feature.\n|-\n| Robo Risk ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||Climbing simulator || Sci-Fi climbing simulator with random level generation and endless gameplay.\n|-\n| YoHoHo ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||[[Arcade game]] || Keep captain Flyn afloat and out of the water as he sails across the sea.\n|-\n| FlapOTron ||2015 ||[[iOS]] ||[[Arcade game]] || The players have to avoid touching the towers using 3D Touch to control the Electron.\n|-\n| Ishi GO ||2015 ||iOS ||[[Arcade game]] || Another addictive game where the players have to dodge through the rocks using 3D Touch control.\n|-\n| Imperial Hero II ||2015||[[Browser game|Browser]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Facebook]] ||[[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]] || The upgraded version of Imperia Online's Imperial hero from 2009.\n|-\n| Game of Emperors ||2016||[[Browser game|Browser]], [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[Facebook]], [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Windows Store]]||[[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]] || The players develop their own cities by constructing economic and military buildings, researching in the University in the Capital and expanding their army, which will fight in the battles.\n|-\n| MedCorps || 2016 || [[iOS]] || Strategy, Simulation || The player has to control a team of specialists, fight diseases, grow his organization and ultimately save the world from dangerous viruses.\n|-\n|Kingdoms Online\n|2017\n|[[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n|[[Massively multiplayer online real-time strategy game|MMORTS]]\n|Adapted mobile version of Imperia Online for the Arabic-speaking players in the MENA region.\n|}\n\n== Training and education ==\nIn 2013 Imperia Online JSC established the first tuition-free school for game developers in Bulgaria. It was originally named Imperial Training Camp and its first season prepared 40 enthusiasts for the professional [[PHP]]/[[MySQL]] and [[Java (programming language)|Java]]/[[Android (operating system)|Android]] fields. 20 of those 40 graduates were hired by Imperia Online JSC, and the rest were recommended to other software companies.\n\nIn 2014 the second season of IO's Training Camp drew even higher interest and this time there were 80 students, divided into 4 groups of 20: 62 graduated, of which 30 were hired by Imperia Online JSC.\n\nFor the third season Imperia Online JSC was joined by another Bulgarian company - Trader.bg - and the school was renamed to \u201cIT Talents Training Camp\u201d. By that time the courses are [[PHP]]/ [[MySQL]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]]/ [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[JavaScript]], [[Objective-C]]/[[iOS]], and [[Java SE]] / [[Java EE]].  In January 2015 the third season ended with a big part of the 115 participants getting hired.\n\nEvery year, there are 180 cadets successfully graduated from the academy. IT Talents Training Camp is already partnering with over 80 companies in the IT industry, to provide them qualified IT specialists. The initiative registers more than 2000 applications per season, from which around 200 most motivated candidates are allowed to enter the intensive 5-month courses. IT Talents is an NGO since 2016 and is provided with Google Ad Grants, enabling free AdWords campaigns. As of November 2017, The Municipality of Burgas organizes a 5-month program in cooperation with IT Talents. The training is again completely free and the applications are done by filling in a short registration form.\n\n== Outsourcing ==\nIn May 2015 Imperia Online JSC founded a private company for IT outsourcing called Imperia Mobile Ltd. Till the end of the year the new unit led by Radoslav Gaydarski had already successfully released more than 10 major projects. The outsourcing company offers a full range of services to execute a technical project and overcome any challenges, relying on the full capacity of over 165 professional developers, designers, artists, QA specialists and business developers. In January 2017 Imperia Mobile Ltd. started a rebranding process to the new name of Upnetix, which was completed in April 2017. The company has over 50 released projects and know-how in more than 10 industries. In September 2018, the company was acquired by one of the leading IT companies in Bulgaria - ScaleFocus.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* {{Official website|www.imperiaonline.bg}}\n\n[[Category:Browser-based game websites]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Bulgaria]]\n", "name_user": "Marry.pavlova", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043d\u0438 \u043b\u0438\u043f\u0441\u0432\u0430\u0449\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0449\u0430.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperia_Online_JSC"}
{"title_page": "Mela Hesen\u00ea Batey\u00ee", "text_new": "'''Mela Hesen\u00ea Batey\u00ee''' ({{lang-ku|Melay\u00ea Batey\u00ee}}, 1417\u20131491) was a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] [[poet]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=leezenberg|first=michiel|date=2014|title=El\u00ee Teremax\u00ee and the vernacularization of medrese learning in Kurdistan|url=|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=47|pages=713\u2013733|via=|doi=10.1080/00210862.2014.934150}}</ref> and [[cleric]]. His real name was ''Hussein''. He belonged to the ''Artushi'' tribe. He was born in ''Bate'', a village in [[Hakkari Province]], in present-day south-eastern [[Turkey]].\n\n==Works==\nHis main work is called ''Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee'' (Birthday in Kurmanji), written in [[Kurmanji]] dialect of [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], a celebration of the birth of [[Muhammad]]. The book contains 19 chapters. It was used as a textbook for teaching Kurdish in the past. It is also very popular among [[Muslim]] Kurds in northern [[Kurdistan]] and many people recite its poems by heart. Its poems are also recited in other occasions such as in charity. This book was published for the first time in 1905 in [[Egypt]]. It was published for the second time in 1919 in [[Istanbul]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20070207061553/http://hem.bredband.net/serkay/Doc/Pirtuk/pirtuk-b/Nr-4.htm ''Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee'', Pencinar Publishers for Kurdish Culture, Sweden, in Kurdish]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405022925/http://www.navkurd.de/edebiyat.htm#bate ''Melay\u00ea Bat\u00ea'' in \"Famous Kurdish poets, writers and philosophers\", NavKurd, in Kurdish ]\n#Mel\u00ea Batey\u00ee, Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee, kurd\u00ee/kurmanc\u00ee, Roja Nu Publishers, Sverige/Stockholm, 1987, 64 r\u00fbpel, {{ISBN|91-7672-018-7}}.\n\n{{Kurdish literature}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bate, Ahmade}}\n[[Category:1417 births]]\n[[Category:1491 deaths]]\n[[Category:Kurdish poets]]\n[[Category:Kurdish philosophers]]\n\n\n{{Kurd-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Mela Hesen\u00ea Batey\u00ee''' or  ([[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]; '''Melay\u00ea Batey\u00ee''') (1417\u20131491) was a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] [[poet]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=leezenberg|first=michiel|date=2014|title=El\u00ee Teremax\u00ee and the vernacularization of medrese learning in Kurdistan|url=|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=47|pages=713\u2013733|via=|doi=10.1080/00210862.2014.934150}}</ref> and [[cleric]]. His real name was ''Hussein''. He belonged to the ''Artushi'' tribe. He was born in ''Bate'', a village in [[Hakkari Province]], in present-day south-eastern [[Turkey]].\n\n==Works==\nHis main work is called ''Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee'' (Birthday in Kurmanji), written in [[Kurmanji]] dialect of [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], a celebration of the birth of [[Muhammad]]. The book contains 19 chapters. It was used as a textbook for teaching Kurdish in the past. It is also very popular among [[Muslim]] Kurds in northern [[Kurdistan]] and many people recite its poems by heart. Its poems are also recited in other occasions such as in charity. This book was published for the first time in 1905 in [[Egypt]]. It was published for the second time in 1919 in [[Istanbul]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20070207061553/http://hem.bredband.net/serkay/Doc/Pirtuk/pirtuk-b/Nr-4.htm ''Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee'', Pencinar Publishers for Kurdish Culture, Sweden, in Kurdish]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405022925/http://www.navkurd.de/edebiyat.htm#bate ''Melay\u00ea Bat\u00ea'' in \"Famous Kurdish poets, writers and philosophers\", NavKurd, in Kurdish ]\n#Mel\u00ea Batey\u00ee, Mewl\u00fbda Kurmanc\u00ee, kurd\u00ee/kurmanc\u00ee, Roja Nu Publishers, Sverige/Stockholm, 1987, 64 r\u00fbpel, {{ISBN|91-7672-018-7}}.\n\n{{Kurdish literature}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bate, Ahmade}}\n[[Category:1417 births]]\n[[Category:1491 deaths]]\n[[Category:Kurdish poets]]\n[[Category:Kurdish philosophers]]\n\n\n{{Kurd-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sems\u00fbr\u00ee", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mela_Hesen%C3%AA_Batey%C3%AE"}
{"title_page": "Jacek Malczewski", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Jacek Malczewski\n| image        = Malczewski Jacek Autoportret z paleta.jpg\n| image_size   = 226px\n| caption      = [[Self-portrait#Gallery: painters at work|Self-portrait]], 1892\n| birth_date    = 15 July 1854\n| birth_place   = [[Radom]], [[Congress Poland]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1929|10|8|1854|7|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]\n| nationality   = Polish\n| field         = Painting\n| movement      = [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]]\n}}\n'''Jacek Malczewski''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8jat\u0361s\u025bk mal\u02c8t\u0361\u0282\u025bfsk\u02b2i|lang|PL-Jacek Malczewski.ogg}}; 15 July 1854 \u2013 8 October 1929) is one of the most revered painters of [[Poland]], associated with the patriotic [[Young Poland]] movement following a [[Partitions of Poland|century of Partitions]]. He is regarded as the father of Polish [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]]. His creative output combined the predominant style of his times, with historical motifs of Polish [[martyrdom]], the romantic ideals of independence, Christian and Greek mythology, folk tales, as well as his love of the natural world.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\">{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416120803/http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-04-16 | title=Jacek Malczewski | publisher=Instytut Sztuki Polskiej Akademii Nauk. Culture.pl | work=Symbolizm w polskim malarstwie prze\u0142omu XIX i XX wieku | date=October 2002 | accessdate=October 17, 2012 | author=Irena Kossowska | language=Polish | quote=Filled with erotic undertones the existentialist trend in Malczewski's art revealed his deep attachment to Polish tradition and his fascination with legend and folklore (Polish: Nasycony erotycznymi podtekstami, egzystencjalny nurt w tw\u00f3rczo\u015bci Malczewskiego... dawa\u0142 wyraz zakorzeniania artysty w rodzimej tradycji, jego fascynacji ludowymi legendami i ba\u015bniami.) }}</ref><ref name=\"info-poland\">{{cite web | url=http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/Malczewski.html | title=Malczewski's Mythology | publisher=University of Buffalo. Info.Poland. | work=Malczewski exhibition at the Czartoryski Museum (Warsaw Voice review). | year=1996 | access-date=October 17, 2012 | author=Marcin Grota | quote=[He produced] paintings showing [[Madonna (art)|Madonnas]] with faces and figures characteristic of the type of beauty that in Malczewski's times could be seen in the villages scattered along the [[Vistula]] river... | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625151131/http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/Malczewski.html | archive-date=June 25, 2010 | df= }}</ref> He was the father of painter [[Rafa\u0142 Malczewski]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Szymalak-Bugajska, Paulina|date=2017|url=https://niezlasztuka.net/o-sztuce/jacek-malczewski-rycerz-polskiej-sztuki/|title=Jacek Malczewski \u2013 rycerz polskiej sztuki|trans-title=Jacek Malczewski - Knight of Polish Art|lang=pl|publisher=niezlasztuka.net|access-date=2020-04-14}} </ref>\n\n==Childhood==\nMalczewski was born in [[Radom]], [[Congress Poland]], under occupation of the Russian Empire. <ref name=\"gazeta.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/1,114873,10109782,Malopolskie__Obrazy_Malczewskich_na_wystawie_w_Zakopanem.html | title=Obrazy Malczewskich na wystawie w Zakopanem | publisher=Gazeta.pl | work=Wiadomo\u015bci | date=August 12, 2011 | access-date=October 19, 2012 | author=PAP | author-link=Polska Agencja Prasowa | language=Polish | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302192920/http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/1,114873,10109782,Malopolskie__Obrazy_Malczewskich_na_wystawie_w_Zakopanem.html | archive-date=March 2, 2014 | df= }}</ref> During his childhood and early youth he was greatly influenced by his father Julian, a Polish patriot and social activist who introduced him to the world of romantic literature inspired by the [[November Uprising]]. On his mother's side, he was related to the [[Theodore de Korwin Szymanowski|Szymanowski]] family whom they often visited on their [[Masovia]]n country estate in [[Cyg\u00f3w]]. The attractiveness of the Polish landscape and associated [[folklore]] had been awakened in him by Feliks Karczewski, his uncle and long-time guardian, who had invited future novelist [[Adolf Dygasi\u0144ski]] to his estate, to act as Jacek's home tutor.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" />\n\n==Artistic career==\n[[File:Malczewski melancholia.jpg|thumb|320px|''Melancholia'' (1894), [[National Museum, Pozna\u0144|National Museum]] in [[Pozna\u0144]]]]\nMalczewski moved to [[Krak\u00f3w]] at age 17, and began his artistic education in 1872 under the watchful eye of Polish painter and draughtsman {{Interlanguage link|Leon Piccard|fr}} and attended his first art classes in the workshop of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw \u0141uszczkiewicz]] at the [[Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts|School of Fine Arts]]. A year later, in 1873, assessed by [[Jan Matejko]] himself, Malczewski formally enrolled at the School, and studied with \u0141uszczkiewicz, Feliks Szynalewski and [[Florian Cynk]]. In 1876 he went to [[Paris]] and studied for a year at the [[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]], in the studio of [[Henri Lehmann]]. He next moved to the [[Acad\u00e9mie Suisse]].<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"gazeta.pl\" />\n\nMalczewski had already begun master classes with Jan Matejko in 1875 before embarking on the trip to France, and completed them in 1879 after his return from abroad. In spite of considerable stylistic differences between them, Malczewski was greatly influenced by Matejko's historical painting filled with [[neo-romantic]] metaphor and patriotic themes. In 1879, Malczewski completed a course in composition under Matejko.<ref>[http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Jacek Malczewski] at [http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Culture.pl]</ref> He was equally impressed with the dramatic art of earlier Polish romantic painter [[Artur Grottger]]. His painting revolved around a few carefully selected motifs, constantly retold and expanded according to mythology and filled with national symbols. His own imagination enabled Malczewski to channel his creativity and let new aesthetic ideas emerge giving rise to what became Poland's school of Symbolism.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" />\n\n===Inspiration===\nOver the course of some 30 years between 1885 and 1916, Malczewski regularly visited Paris, [[Munich]] and [[Vienna]]. He made several trips to [[Italy]], [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]]. He also took part in an archaeological expedition organized by his friend [[Karol Lanckoro\u0144ski]]. He drew his inspiration from a wide variety of sources often exotic or biblical, and translated them back into Polish folklore, tradition and motifs in his own painting.<ref name=\"info-poland\" /> His most famous canvases include ''B\u0142\u0119dne ko\u0142o'' (Vicious Circle, 1895\u201397), ''Melancholia'' (1890\u20131894), ''Natchnienie malarza'' (Painter's Muse, 1897), ''Wizja'' (A vision, 1912), the ''[[Thanatos]]'' series, and ''Bajki'' (Fables). Many of his paintings prominently feature self-portraits in elaborate costume, a trademark of his style, often displaying a great sense of self-mocking humour.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"info-poland\" />\n\nIn 1897\u20131900 and 1912\u20131921 Malczewski served as professor of the [[Academy of Fine Arts in Krak\u00f3w]].<ref name=\"zascianek.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_J/Malczewski_J_bio.htm | title=Jacek Malczewski (Radom 1854 - Krak\u00f3w 1929) | publisher=Pinakoteka Zascianek.pl | work=Short biography | accessdate=October 18, 2012 | language=Polish | quote=''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'', Warsaw 1974.}}</ref> He was elected Rector of the Academy in 1912.<ref name=\"Onet.Kultura\">{{cite web | url=http://m.onet.pl/wiedza-swiat/kultura,tl54y | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416095305/http://m.onet.pl/wiedza-swiat/kultura,tl54y | url-status=dead | archive-date=April 16, 2013 | title=Biografia Jacka Malczewskiego | publisher=Onet.Kultura | work=Malczewski. Dukt pisma i p\u0119dzla | date=September 4, 2012 | access-date=November 16, 2012 | author=Polish Press Agency | author-link=Polish Press Agency | language=Polish }}</ref> His art has been compared to that of the Frenchman [[Gustave Moreau]], the Swiss [[Arnold B\u00f6cklin]], and even to the Spaniard [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. His paintings won numerous awards at international exhibitions including [[Berlin]] in 1891, Munich in 1892, and Paris in 1900.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"info-poland\" /> \n\n==Personal life==\nMalczewski was married to Maria ''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Garlewska and they had two children, Julia (born 1888) and Rafa\u0142 (born 1892), also a painter. His son later sold off all of his father's works left to him, to the [[National Museum in Warsaw]] before [[World War II]]. During the war he left Poland and after travels in Southern Europe and [[Brazil]], finally settled in [[Montreal]]. \n\nIt is believed that the subject of numerous nude studies in Jacek Malczewski's paintings, [[Maria Bal]] (Balowa) ''n\u00e9e'' Brunicka, was also his long-time lover.<ref name=\"gazeta-2\">{{cite web | url=http://wyborcza.pl/alehistoria/1,128610,12485624,Malczewski_u_zrodla.html | title=Malczewski u \u017ar\u00f3d\u0142a | publisher=[[Gazeta Wyborcza]] | work=Ale historia | date=September 14, 2012 | accessdate=October 19, 2012 | author=W\u0142odzimierz Kalicki | language=Polish}}</ref> He lost his sight towards the end of his life and died in Krak\u00f3w on October 8, 1929. He was buried at [[Ska\u0142ka]], Poland's national ''[[Panth\u00e9on, Paris|Panth\u00e9on]]''.<ref name=\"gazeta.pl\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n{{Gallery|width=165|height=150|lines=1|align=center|perrow=4 \n|File:Jacek Malczewski - Polish Hamlet - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Polish Hamlet. Portrait of Aleksander Wielopolski|Poland's Hamlet]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Chrystus i Samarytanka 2.jpg|''Christ and [[Samaritan woman at the well]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Tobiasz i Parki.jpg|''[[Book of Tobit|Tobias]] and [[Parcae]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Pokusa fortuny.jpg|''Temptation of Fortune''\n}}\n{{Gallery|width=165|height=150|lines=1|align=center \n|File:Bledne kolo.jpg|''B\u0142\u0119dne ko\u0142o'' (Vicious Circle)\n|File:Malczewski wigilia na syberii.jpg|''[[Sybirak|Siberian]] [[Wigilia]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Ojczyzna.jpg|''Motherland''. <small>Portrait of </small>[[Maria Bal]]\n|File:Malczewski_Thanatos.jpg|''[[Thanatos]]''\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons|Jacek Malczewski|Paintings by Jacek Malczewski}}\n{{Commons category|Jacek Malczewski}}\n* [[Sukiennice Museum]] in  [[Krak\u00f3w]]\n* [[National Museum, Krak\u00f3w]]\n* [[Culture of Krak\u00f3w]]\n* City of [[Radom]]\n* [[List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_J/Malczewski_J_5.htm Paintings of Jacek Malczewski] at Zascianek.pl\n*[http://muzeumsecesji.pl/galeria_pliki/malczewski/malczewski1.html Virtual Art Nouveau museum - Jacek Malczewski] at Muzeum Secesji.pl\n*[http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Culture.pl]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malczewski, Jacek}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Radom]]\n[[Category:People from Radom Governorate]]\n[[Category:19th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Symbolist painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the \u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]]\n[[Category:Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Jacek Malczewski\n| image        = Malczewski Jacek Autoportret z paleta.jpg\n| image_size   = 226px\n| caption      = [[Self-portrait#Gallery: painters at work|Self-portrait]], 1892\n| birth_date    = 15 July 1854\n| birth_place   = [[Radom]], [[Congress Poland]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1929|10|8|1854|7|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]\n| nationality   = Polish\n| field         = Painting\n| movement      = [[Symbolism]]\n}}\n'''Jacek Malczewski''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8jat\u0361s\u025bk mal\u02c8t\u0361\u0282\u025bfsk\u02b2i|lang|PL-Jacek Malczewski.ogg}}; 15 July 1854 \u2013 8 October 1929) is one of the most revered painters of [[Poland]], associated with the patriotic [[Young Poland]] movement following a [[Partitions of Poland|century of Partitions]]. He is regarded as the father of Polish [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]]. His creative output combined the predominant style of his times, with historical motifs of Polish [[martyrdom]], the romantic ideals of independence, Christian and Greek mythology, folk tales, as well as his love of the natural world.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\">{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416120803/http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-04-16 | title=Jacek Malczewski | publisher=Instytut Sztuki Polskiej Akademii Nauk. Culture.pl | work=Symbolizm w polskim malarstwie prze\u0142omu XIX i XX wieku | date=October 2002 | accessdate=October 17, 2012 | author=Irena Kossowska | language=Polish | quote=Filled with erotic undertones the existentialist trend in Malczewski's art revealed his deep attachment to Polish tradition and his fascination with legend and folklore (Polish: Nasycony erotycznymi podtekstami, egzystencjalny nurt w tw\u00f3rczo\u015bci Malczewskiego... dawa\u0142 wyraz zakorzeniania artysty w rodzimej tradycji, jego fascynacji ludowymi legendami i ba\u015bniami.) }}</ref><ref name=\"info-poland\">{{cite web | url=http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/Malczewski.html | title=Malczewski's Mythology | publisher=University of Buffalo. Info.Poland. | work=Malczewski exhibition at the Czartoryski Museum (Warsaw Voice review). | year=1996 | access-date=October 17, 2012 | author=Marcin Grota | quote=[He produced] paintings showing [[Madonna (art)|Madonnas]] with faces and figures characteristic of the type of beauty that in Malczewski's times could be seen in the villages scattered along the [[Vistula]] river... | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625151131/http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/Malczewski.html | archive-date=June 25, 2010 | df= }}</ref> He was the father of painter [[Rafa\u0142 Malczewski]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Szymalak-Bugajska, Paulina|date=2017|url=https://niezlasztuka.net/o-sztuce/jacek-malczewski-rycerz-polskiej-sztuki/|title=Jacek Malczewski \u2013 rycerz polskiej sztuki|trans-title=Jacek Malczewski - Knight of Polish Art|lang=pl|publisher=niezlasztuka.net|access-date=2020-04-14}} </ref>\n\n==Childhood==\nMalczewski was born in [[Radom]], [[Congress Poland]], under occupation of the Russian Empire. <ref name=\"gazeta.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/1,114873,10109782,Malopolskie__Obrazy_Malczewskich_na_wystawie_w_Zakopanem.html | title=Obrazy Malczewskich na wystawie w Zakopanem | publisher=Gazeta.pl | work=Wiadomo\u015bci | date=August 12, 2011 | access-date=October 19, 2012 | author=PAP | author-link=Polska Agencja Prasowa | language=Polish | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302192920/http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/1,114873,10109782,Malopolskie__Obrazy_Malczewskich_na_wystawie_w_Zakopanem.html | archive-date=March 2, 2014 | df= }}</ref> During his childhood and early youth he was greatly influenced by his father Julian, a Polish patriot and social activist who introduced him to the world of romantic literature inspired by the [[November Uprising]]. On his mother's side, he was related to the [[Theodore de Korwin Szymanowski|Szymanowski]] family whom they often visited on their [[Masovia]]n country estate in [[Cyg\u00f3w]]. The attractiveness of the Polish landscape and associated [[folklore]] had been awakened in him by Feliks Karczewski, his uncle and long-time guardian, who had invited future novelist [[Adolf Dygasi\u0144ski]] to his estate, to act as Jacek's home tutor.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" />\n\n==Artistic career==\n[[File:Malczewski melancholia.jpg|thumb|320px|''Melancholia'' (1894), [[National Museum, Pozna\u0144|National Museum]] in [[Pozna\u0144]]]]\nMalczewski moved to [[Krak\u00f3w]] at age 17, and began his artistic education in 1872 under the watchful eye of Polish painter and draughtsman {{Interlanguage link|Leon Piccard|fr}} and attended his first art classes in the workshop of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw \u0141uszczkiewicz]] at the [[Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts|School of Fine Arts]]. A year later, in 1873, assessed by [[Jan Matejko]] himself, Malczewski formally enrolled at the School, and studied with \u0141uszczkiewicz, Feliks Szynalewski and [[Florian Cynk]]. In 1876 he went to [[Paris]] and studied for a year at the [[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]], in the studio of [[Henri Lehmann]]. He next moved to the [[Acad\u00e9mie Suisse]].<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"gazeta.pl\" />\n\nMalczewski had already begun master classes with Jan Matejko in 1875 before embarking on the trip to France, and completed them in 1879 after his return from abroad. In spite of considerable stylistic differences between them, Malczewski was greatly influenced by Matejko's historical painting filled with [[neo-romantic]] metaphor and patriotic themes. In 1879, Malczewski completed a course in composition under Matejko.<ref>[http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Jacek Malczewski] at [http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Culture.pl]</ref> He was equally impressed with the dramatic art of earlier Polish romantic painter [[Artur Grottger]]. His painting revolved around a few carefully selected motifs, constantly retold and expanded according to mythology and filled with national symbols. His own imagination enabled Malczewski to channel his creativity and let new aesthetic ideas emerge giving rise to what became Poland's school of Symbolism.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" />\n\n===Inspiration===\nOver the course of some 30 years between 1885 and 1916, Malczewski regularly visited Paris, [[Munich]] and [[Vienna]]. He made several trips to [[Italy]], [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]]. He also took part in an archaeological expedition organized by his friend [[Karol Lanckoro\u0144ski]]. He drew his inspiration from a wide variety of sources often exotic or biblical, and translated them back into Polish folklore, tradition and motifs in his own painting.<ref name=\"info-poland\" /> His most famous canvases include ''B\u0142\u0119dne ko\u0142o'' (Vicious Circle, 1895\u201397), ''Melancholia'' (1890\u20131894), ''Natchnienie malarza'' (Painter's Muse, 1897), ''Wizja'' (A vision, 1912), the ''[[Thanatos]]'' series, and ''Bajki'' (Fables). Many of his paintings prominently feature self-portraits in elaborate costume, a trademark of his style, often displaying a great sense of self-mocking humour.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"info-poland\" />\n\nIn 1897\u20131900 and 1912\u20131921 Malczewski served as professor of the [[Academy of Fine Arts in Krak\u00f3w]].<ref name=\"zascianek.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_J/Malczewski_J_bio.htm | title=Jacek Malczewski (Radom 1854 - Krak\u00f3w 1929) | publisher=Pinakoteka Zascianek.pl | work=Short biography | accessdate=October 18, 2012 | language=Polish | quote=''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'', Warsaw 1974.}}</ref> He was elected Rector of the Academy in 1912.<ref name=\"Onet.Kultura\">{{cite web | url=http://m.onet.pl/wiedza-swiat/kultura,tl54y | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416095305/http://m.onet.pl/wiedza-swiat/kultura,tl54y | url-status=dead | archive-date=April 16, 2013 | title=Biografia Jacka Malczewskiego | publisher=Onet.Kultura | work=Malczewski. Dukt pisma i p\u0119dzla | date=September 4, 2012 | access-date=November 16, 2012 | author=Polish Press Agency | author-link=Polish Press Agency | language=Polish }}</ref> His art has been compared to that of the Frenchman [[Gustave Moreau]], the Swiss [[Arnold B\u00f6cklin]], and even to the Spaniard [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. His paintings won numerous awards at international exhibitions including [[Berlin]] in 1891, Munich in 1892, and Paris in 1900.<ref name=\"baza-sztuki\" /><ref name=\"info-poland\" /> \n\n==Personal life==\nMalczewski was married to Maria ''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Garlewska and they had two children, Julia (born 1888) and Rafa\u0142 (born 1892), also a painter. His son later sold off all of his father's works left to him, to the [[National Museum in Warsaw]] before [[World War II]]. During the war he left Poland and after travels in Southern Europe and [[Brazil]], finally settled in [[Montreal]]. \n\nIt is believed that the subject of numerous nude studies in Jacek Malczewski's paintings, [[Maria Bal]] (Balowa) ''n\u00e9e'' Brunicka, was also his long-time lover.<ref name=\"gazeta-2\">{{cite web | url=http://wyborcza.pl/alehistoria/1,128610,12485624,Malczewski_u_zrodla.html | title=Malczewski u \u017ar\u00f3d\u0142a | publisher=[[Gazeta Wyborcza]] | work=Ale historia | date=September 14, 2012 | accessdate=October 19, 2012 | author=W\u0142odzimierz Kalicki | language=Polish}}</ref> He lost his sight towards the end of his life and died in Krak\u00f3w on October 8, 1929. He was buried at [[Ska\u0142ka]], Poland's national ''[[Panth\u00e9on, Paris|Panth\u00e9on]]''.<ref name=\"gazeta.pl\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n{{Gallery|width=165|height=150|lines=1|align=center|perrow=4 \n|File:Jacek Malczewski - Polish Hamlet - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Polish Hamlet. Portrait of Aleksander Wielopolski|Poland's Hamlet]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Chrystus i Samarytanka 2.jpg|''Christ and [[Samaritan woman at the well]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Tobiasz i Parki.jpg|''[[Book of Tobit|Tobias]] and [[Parcae]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Pokusa fortuny.jpg|''Temptation of Fortune''\n}}\n{{Gallery|width=165|height=150|lines=1|align=center \n|File:Bledne kolo.jpg|''B\u0142\u0119dne ko\u0142o'' (Vicious Circle)\n|File:Malczewski wigilia na syberii.jpg|''[[Sybirak|Siberian]] [[Wigilia]]''\n|File:Malczewski Jacek Ojczyzna.jpg|''Motherland''. <small>Portrait of </small>[[Maria Bal]]\n|File:Malczewski_Thanatos.jpg|''[[Thanatos]]''\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons|Jacek Malczewski|Paintings by Jacek Malczewski}}\n{{Commons category|Jacek Malczewski}}\n* [[Sukiennice Museum]] in  [[Krak\u00f3w]]\n* [[National Museum, Krak\u00f3w]]\n* [[Culture of Krak\u00f3w]]\n* City of [[Radom]]\n* [[List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_J/Malczewski_J_5.htm Paintings of Jacek Malczewski] at Zascianek.pl\n*[http://muzeumsecesji.pl/galeria_pliki/malczewski/malczewski1.html Virtual Art Nouveau museum - Jacek Malczewski] at Muzeum Secesji.pl\n*[http://culture.pl/en/artist/jacek-malczewski Culture.pl]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malczewski, Jacek}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Radom]]\n[[Category:People from Radom Governorate]]\n[[Category:19th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Symbolist painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the \u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]]\n[[Category:Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSymbolism(link changed toSymbolism (arts)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacek_Malczewski"}
{"title_page": "Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov", "text_new": "{{short description|Chess matches between Deep Blue and Kasparov}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = [[File:Chess klt45.svg|30px]] Deep Blue vs. Kasparov\n| header_align = center\n| header_background = \n| footer = '''First match'''\n* February 10, 1996: took place in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n* Result: '''Kasparov'''\u2013Deep Blue (4\u20132)\n* Record set: First computer program to defeat a world champion in a ''{{chessgloss|classical}} game'' under tournament regulations\n\n'''Second match (rematch)'''\n* May 11, 1997: held in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Result: '''Deep Blue'''\u2013Kasparov (3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd)\n* Record set: First computer program to defeat a world champion in a ''match'' under tournament regulations\n| footer_align = left\n| footer_background = \n| width = \n| image1 = Deep Blue.jpg\n| width1 = 160\n| caption1 = [[Deep Blue (chess computer)|Deep Blue]] <br /><small>[[IBM]] [[Computer chess|chess computer]]</small>\n| image2 = Kasparov-29.jpg\n| width2 = 160\n| caption2 = [[Garry Kasparov]] <br /><small>[[World Chess Champion]]</small>\n| caption_align = center\n}}\n\n'''Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov''' was a pair of six-game [[chess]] matches between world chess champion [[Garry Kasparov]] and an IBM supercomputer called [[Deep Blue (chess computer)|Deep Blue]].  The first match was played in Philadelphia in 1996 and won by Kasparov.   The second was played in New York City in 1997 and won by Deep Blue.  The 1997 match was the first defeat of a reigning world chess champion by a computer under tournament conditions.\n\nThe 1997 match was the subject of a documentary film, ''The Man vs. The Machine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=11694550 |title=Signals: The Man vs. The Machine |last1= |website=espn.go.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=2014-10-24}}</ref>\n{{algebraic notation|pos=toc}}\n\n==Symbolic significance==\nDeep Blue's win was seen as symbolically significant, a sign that artificial intelligence was catching up to human intelligence, and could defeat one of humanity's great intellectual champions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Be Afraid|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/be-afraid/article/9802|publisher=www.weeklystandard.com|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=26 May 1997}}</ref> Later analysis tended to play down Kasparov's loss as a result of uncharacteristically bad play on Kasparov's part, and play down the intellectual value of chess as a game that can be defeated by brute force.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Somers|first1=James|title=The Man Who Would Teach Machines to Think|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2013/11/the-man-who-would-teach-machines-to-think/309529/|accessdate=28 September 2016|publisher=www.theatlantic.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Finley|first1=Klint|title=Did a Computer Bug Help Deep Blue Beat Kasparov?|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/09/deep-blue-computer-bug/|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, discussing the match in a podcast with neuroscientist Sam Harris, Kasparov advised of a change of heart in his views of this match. Kasparov stated: \"While writing the book I did a lot of research \u2013 analysing the games with modern computers, also soul-searching \u2013 and I changed my conclusions. I am not writing any love letters to IBM, but my respect for the Deep Blue team went up, and my opinion of my own play, and Deep Blue's play, went down. Today you can buy a chess engine for your laptop that will beat Deep Blue quite easily.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/kasparov-on-the-future-of-artificial-intelligence|title=Kasparov on the future of Artificial Intelligence|date=2016-12-29|newspaper=Chess News|access-date=2016-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDeep Blue's victory switched the canonical example of a game where humans outmatched machines to the ancient Chinese game of [[Go (game)|Go]], a game of simple rules and far more possible moves than chess, which requires more intuition and is less susceptible to brute force.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Electronic Holy War|url=http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/the-electronic-holy-war|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=25 March 2014}}</ref> Go is widely played in China, South Korea, and Japan, and was considered one of the [[four arts of the Chinese scholar]] in antiquity. [[Go programs]] were able to defeat only amateur players until 2015, when Google DeepMind's [[AlphaGo]] program surprisingly defeated [[Lee Sedol]] in the match [[AlphaGo versus Lee Sedol]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Byford|first1=Sam|title=DeepMind's AlphaGo secures victory over Lee Se-dol with third straight win|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/12/11210650/alphago-deepmind-go-match-3-result|website=The Verge|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=12 March 2016}}</ref> While Deep Blue mainly relied on brute computational force to evaluate millions of positions, AlphaGo also relied on [[neural network]]s and [[reinforcement learning]].\n\n==Summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=left\n|+ The 1996 match\n|-\n!Game #\n!White\n!Black\n!Result\n!Comment\n|-\n| 1 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130||\n|-\n| 2 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n| 3 || Deep Blue || Kasparov || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || [[Draw by agreement|Draw by mutual agreement]]\n|-\n| 4 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n| 5 || Deep Blue || '''Kasparov''' || 0\u20131 || Kasparov offered a draw after the 23rd move.\n|-\n| 6 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | ''Result:'' Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue: 4\u20132\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=left\n|+The 1997 rematch\n|-\n!Game #\n!White\n!Black\n!Result\n!Comment\n|-\n|1 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n|2 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n|3 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|4 || Deep Blue || Kasparov || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|5 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|6 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | ''Result:'' Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov: 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==1996 match==\n\n===Game 1 {{anchor|1996 Game 1}}===\n{{main article|Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1}}\n{{Chess diagram \n |tright\n |'''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1996, rd 1'''\n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |rl\n |  |  |  |  |  |qd|  |kd\n |  |  |  |ql|  |  |nl|  \n |  |  |  |pd|  |  |  |  \n |pl|pl|  |  |  |pd|pl|pl\n |  |  |  |  |  |nd|  |kl\n |  |  |  |  |rd|  |  |  \n |Final position after 37.Rxh7{{chessAN|+}}\n}}\n''February 10''. The first game of the 1996 match was the first game to be won by a [[Computer chess|chess-playing computer]] against a reigning [[World Chess Championship|world champion]] under normal chess tournament conditions, and in particular, {{chessgloss|classical}} [[time control]]s.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c5 2.c3 d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.Be2 e6 7.h3 Bh5 8.0-0 Nc6 9.Be3 cxd4 10.cxd4 Bb4 11.a3 Ba5 12.Nc3 Qd6 13.Nb5 Qe7 14.Ne5 Bxe2 15.Qxe2 0-0 16.Rac1 Rac8 17.Bg5 Bb6 18.Bxf6 gxf6 19.Nc4 Rfd8 20.Nxb6 axb6 21.Rfd1 f5 22.Qe3 Qf6 23.d5 Rxd5 24.Rxd5 exd5 25.b3 Kh8 26.Qxb6 Rg8 27.Qc5 d4 28.Nd6 f4 29.Nxb7 Ne5 30.Qd5 f3 31.g3 Nd3 32.Rc7 Re8 33.Nd6 Re1+ 34.Kh2 Nxf2 35.Nxf7+ Kg7 36.Ng5+ Kh6 37.Rxh7+ {{chessAN|1\u20130}}}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Game 2 {{anchor|1996 Game 2}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n |'''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1996, rd 2''' \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |kd|  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |bl|  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |pd|  |pl|  |pl\n |  |  |  |  |bd|  |pl|  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |kl|  |  \n |Final position after 73.Bb5\n}}\n''February 11''. The second game began with the Open [[Catalan Opening]]. Kasparov played in what could be called a preemptive style blocking all Deep Blue's {{chessgloss|development}} attempts. The game lasted for 73 moves but eventually Deep Blue's operator had to [[Resignation|resign]] the game for the computer in a position where both players had a bishop but Kasparov had three pawns to Deep Blue's one.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 e6 3.g3 c5 4.Bg2 Nc6 5.0-0 Nf6 6.c4 dxc4 7.Ne5 Bd7 8.Na3 cxd4 9.Naxc4 Bc5 10.Qb3 0-0 11.Qxb7 Nxe5 12.Nxe5 Rb8 13.Qf3 Bd6 14.Nc6 Bxc6 15.Qxc6 e5 16.Rb1 Rb6 17.Qa4 Qb8 18.Bg5 Be7 19.b4 Bxb4 20.Bxf6 gxf6 21.Qd7 Qc8 22.Qxa7 Rb8 23.Qa4 Bc3 24.Rxb8 Qxb8 25.Be4 Qc7 26.Qa6 Kg7 27.Qd3 Rb8 28.Bxh7 Rb2 29.Be4 Rxa2 30.h4 Qc8 31.Qf3 Ra1 32.Rxa1 Bxa1 33.Qh5 Qh8 34.Qg4+ Kf8 35.Qc8+ Kg7 36.Qg4+ Kf8 37.Bd5 Ke7 38.Bc6 Kf8 39.Bd5 Ke7 40.Qf3 Bc3 41.Bc4 Qc8 42.Qd5 Qe6 43.Qb5 Qd7 44.Qc5+ Qd6 45.Qa7+ Qd7 46.Qa8 Qc7 47.Qa3+ Qd6 48.Qa2 f5 49.Bxf7 e4 50.Bh5 Qf6 51.Qa3+ Kd7 52.Qa7+ Kd8 53.Qb8+ Kd7 54.Be8+ Ke7 55.Bb5 Bd2 56.Qc7+ Kf8 57.Bc4 Bc3 58.Kg2 Be1 59.Kf1 Bc3 60.f4 exf3 61.exf3 Bd2 62.f4 Ke8 63.Qc8+ Ke7 64.Qc5+ Kd8 65.Bd3 Be3 66.Qxf5 Qc6 67.Qf8+ Kc7 68.Qe7+ Kc8 69.Bf5+ Kb8 70.Qd8+ Kb7 71.Qd7+ Qxd7 72.Bxd7 Kc7 73.Bb5 1\u20130}}\n\n===Game 3 {{anchor|1996 Game 3}}===\n''February 13''. In the third game Kasparov played the [[Sicilian Defence]] to which Deep Blue responded with the [[Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation|Alapin Variation]]. The game lasted for 39 moves and was drawn.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c5 2.c3 d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.Be2 e6 7.0-0 Nc6 8.Be3 cxd4 9.cxd4 Bb4 10.a3 Ba5 11.Nc3 Qd6 12.Ne5 Bxe2 13.Qxe2 Bxc3 14.bxc3 Nxe5 15.Bf4 Nf3+ 16.Qxf3 Qd5 17.Qd3 Rc8 18.Rfc1 Qc4 19.Qxc4 Rxc4 20.Rcb1 b6 21.Bb8 Ra4 22.Rb4 Ra5 23.Rc4 0-0 24.Bd6 Ra8 25.Rc6 b5 26.Kf1 Ra4 27.Rb1 a6 28.Ke2 h5 29.Kd3 Rd8 30.Be7 Rd7 31.Bxf6 gxf6 32.Rb3 Kg7 33.Ke3 e5 34.g3 exd4+ 35.cxd4 Re7+ 36.Kf3 Rd7 37.Rd3 Raxd4 38.Rxd4 Rxd4 39.Rxa6 b4 {{chessAN|\u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}}}\n\n===Game 4 {{anchor|1996 Game 4}}===\n''February 14''. The fourth game was the second game to end in a draw, even though at one point Deep Blue's team refused Kasparov's [[Draw by agreement|draw offer]]. The opening played was the [[Semi-Slav Defense]].\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 c6 3.c4 e6 4.Nbd2 Nf6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 Bd6 7.e4 dxe4 8.Nxe4 Nxe4 9.Bxe4 0-0 10.0-0 h6 11.Bc2 e5 12.Re1 exd4 13.Qxd4 Bc5 14.Qc3 a5 15.a3 Nf6 16.Be3 Bxe3 17.Rxe3 Bg4 18.Ne5 Re8 19.Rae1 Be6 20.f4 Qc8 21.h3 b5 22.f5 Bxc4 23.Nxc4 bxc4 24.Rxe8+ Nxe8 25.Re4 Nf6 26.Rxc4 Nd5 27.Qe5 Qd7 28.Rg4 f6 29.Qd4 Kh7 30.Re4 Rd8 31.Kh1 Qc7 32.Qf2 Qb8 33.Ba4 c5 34.Bc6 c4 35.Rxc4 Nb4 36.Bf3 Nd3 37.Qh4 Qxb2 38.Qg3 Qxa3 39.Rc7 Qf8 40.Ra7 Ne5 41.Rxa5 Qf7 42.Rxe5 fxe5 43.Qxe5 Re8 44.Qf4 Qf6 45.Bh5 Rf8 46.Bg6+ Kh8 47.Qc7 Qd4 48.Kh2 Ra8 49.Bh5 Qf6 50.Bg6 Rg8 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 5 {{anchor|1996 Game 5}}===\n''February 16''. The fifth game was the turning point of the match. During the game, Kasparov, playing Black, chose a different opening, the [[Four Knights Game]], from the [[Sicilian Defence]] he had played in games one and three and came out on top. This game was particularly embarrassing for the Deep Blue team, because they had declined Kasparov's draw offer after the 23rd move. This was the only game in the match that Black won.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bb4 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.exd5 cxd5 9.0-0 0-0 10.Bg5 c6 11.Qf3 Be7 12.Rae1 Re8 13.Ne2 h6 14.Bf4 Bd6 15.Nd4 Bg4 16.Qg3 Bxf4 17.Qxf4 Qb6 18.c4 Bd7 19.cxd5 cxd5 20.Rxe8+ Rxe8 21.Qd2 Ne4 22.Bxe4 dxe4 23.b3 Rd8 {{chessAN|({{=}})}} 24.Qc3 f5 25.Rd1 Be6 26.Qe3 Bf7 27.Qc3 f4 28.Rd2 Qf6 29.g3 Rd5 30.a3 Kh7 31.Kg2 Qe5 32.f3 e3 33.Rd3 e2 34.gxf4 e1=Q 35.fxe5 Qxc3 36.Rxc3 Rxd4 37.b4 Bc4 38.Kf2 g5 39.Re3 Be6 40.Rc3 Bc4 41.Re3 Rd2+ 42.Ke1 Rd3 43.Kf2 Kg6 44.Rxd3 Bxd3 45.Ke3 Bc2 46.Kd4 Kf5 47.Kd5 h5 {{chessAN|0\u20131}}}}\n\n===Game 6 {{anchor|1996 Game 6}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1996, rd 6''' \n |rd|bd|rd|  |  |  |  | \n |  |qd|  |  |  |pd|  | \n |pd|pl|pd|  |pd|bl|pd|kd\n |pl|  |ql|pd|pl|  |  |pd\n |  |rl|  |  |  |  |  |pl\n |  |  |  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |pl|  | \n |  |  |rl|  |  |  |kl| \n |Final position after 43.Rb4\n}}\n''February 17''. The sixth game was an illustration of just how badly chess engines could play in some positions at the time. Employing anti-computer tactics and keeping the focus of the game on long-term planning, Kasparov slowly improved his position throughout the mid-game while Deep Blue wasted time doing very little to improve its position. By the end of the game, Deep Blue's pieces were crammed into its queenside corner, with no moves to make aside from shuffling its king. Kasparov had all the time in the world to finish the rout.<ref>{{Citation |last=Burgess |first=Graham |authorlink=Graham Burgess |title=The Mammoth Book of Chess |year=2010 |edition= |publisher=Running Press |id= |pages=}}</ref> Kasparov's next move would probably have been 44.Qe7 to exchange the queens. That would have allowed his pawn, which was about to [[promotion (chess)|promote]], to advance.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.chesscafe.com/text/kibitz91.pdf | title=How Much Longer Can Man Match the Computer? | publisher=Chesscafe.com | author=Tim Harding | work=The Kibitzer | accessdate=2008-02-09 |format = 118 [[kilobyte|kB]] [[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 c6 3.c4 e6 4.Nbd2 Nf6 5.e3 c5 6.b3 Nc6 7.Bb2 cxd4 8.exd4 Be7 9.Rc1 0-0 10.Bd3 Bd7 11.0-0 Nh5 12.Re1 Nf4 13.Bb1 Bd6 14.g3 Ng6 15.Ne5 Rc8 16.Nxd7 Qxd7 17.Nf3 Bb4 18.Re3 Rfd8 19.h4 Nge7 20.a3 Ba5 21.b4 Bc7 22.c5 Re8 23.Qd3 g6 24.Re2 Nf5 25.Bc3 h5 26.b5 Nce7 27.Bd2 Kg7 28.a4 Ra8 29.a5 a6 30.b6 Bb8 31.Bc2 Nc6 32.Ba4 Re7 33.Bc3 Ne5 34.dxe5 Qxa4 35.Nd4 Nxd4 36.Qxd4 Qd7 37.Bd2 Re8 38.Bg5 Rc8 39.Bf6+ Kh7 40.c6 bxc6 41.Qc5 Kh6 42.Rb2 Qb7 43.Rb4 1\u20130}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==1997 rematch==\n\n===Game 1 {{anchor|1997 Game 1}}===\n''May 3''. The 1997 rematch began with the [[King's Indian Attack]], which led Kasparov to victory in 45 moves.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.b3 Nd7 4.Bb2 e6 5.Bg2 Ngf6 6.0-0 c6 7.d3 Bd6 8.Nbd2 0-0 9.h3 Bh5 10.e3 h6 11.Qe1 Qa5 12.a3 Bc7 13.Nh4 g5 14.Nhf3 e5 15.e4 Rfe8 16.Nh2 Qb6 17.Qc1 a5 18.Re1 Bd6 19.Ndf1 dxe4 20.dxe4 Bc5 21.Ne3 Rad8 22.Nhf1 g4 23.hxg4 Nxg4 24.f3 Nxe3 25.Nxe3 Be7 26.Kh1 Bg5 27.Re2 a4 28.b4 f5 29.exf5 e4 30.f4 Bxe2 31.fxg5 Ne5 32.g6 Bf3 33.Bc3 Qb5 34.Qf1 Qxf1+ 35.Rxf1 h5 36.Kg1 Kf8 37.Bh3 b5 38.Kf2 Kg7 39.g4 Kh6 40.Rg1 hxg4 41.Bxg4 Bxg4 42.Nxg4+ Nxg4+ 43.Rxg4 Rd5 44.f6 Rd1 45.g7 1\u20130}}\n\nDeep Blue's 44th move in this game was allegedly the result of a [[bug (software)|bug]] in which Deep Blue, unable to determine a desirable move, resorted to a fail-safe.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.cnet.com/news/did-a-bug-in-deep-blue-lead-to-kasparovs-defeat/ | title=Did a bug in Deep Blue lead to Kasparov's defeat? | publisher=cnet.com | author=Tim Hornyak | accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> [[Nate Silver]] proposes that Kasparov \"concluded that the counterintuitive play must be a sign of superior intelligence\", leading him to lose the second game.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|title=Thinking Machines: The Search for Artificial Intelligence|journal=Distillations |date=2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=14\u201323|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>Silver, Nate. ''[[The Signal and the Noise|The Signal and the Noise: Why so Many Predictions Fail\u2014but Some Don't]].'' New York: Penguin, 2012. Print.</ref>\n\n===Game 2 {{anchor|1997 Game 2}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1997, rd 2''' \n |  |rd|  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |  |  |  |  |kd|pd| \n |rl|qd|ql|bd|  |pd|  |pd\n |  |pd|  |pl|pd|pl|  |\n |  |pl|pd|  |bl|  |  |\n |  |  |pl|  |  |  |  |pl \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |kl|  | \n |Final position after 45.Ra6\n}}\n''May 4.'' The game started with the [[Ruy Lopez]] opening, [[Ruy Lopez#Smyslov Variation|Smyslov Variation]]. Kasparov eventually resigned, although post-game analysis indicates that he could have held a draw in the final position. After this game Kasparov accused IBM of cheating, by alleging that a grandmaster (presumably a top rival) had been behind a certain move. The claim was repeated in the documentary ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117921798.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine|author=Robert Koehler|date=2003-09-09|publisher=Variety|accessdate=2008-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/deep-blue-s-cheating-move|title=Deep Blue's cheating move|date=2015-02-19|website=Chess News|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-28}}</ref> \n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.0-0 Be7 6.Re1 b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 0-0 9.h3 h6 10.d4 Re8 11.Nbd2 Bf8 12.Nf1 Bd7 13.Ng3 Na5 14.Bc2 c5 15.b3 Nc6 16.d5 Ne7 17.Be3 Ng6 18.Qd2 Nh7 19.a4 Nh4 20.Nxh4 Qxh4 21.Qe2 Qd8 22.b4 Qc7 23.Rec1 c4 24.Ra3 Rec8 25.Rca1 Qd8 26.f4 Nf6 27.fxe5 dxe5 28.Qf1 Ne8 29.Qf2 Nd6 30.Bb6 Qe8 31.R3a2 Be7 32.Bc5 Bf8 33.Nf5 Bxf5 34.exf5 f6 35.Bxd6 Bxd6 36.axb5 axb5 37.Be4 Rxa2 38.Qxa2 Qd7 39.Qa7 Rc7 40.Qb6 Rb7 41.Ra8+ Kf7 42.Qa6 Qc7 43.Qc6 Qb6+ 44.Kf1 Rb8 45.Ra6 1\u20130}}\n\nAt the time it was reported that Kasparov missed the fact that after 45...Qe3 46.Qxd6 Re8, Black (Kasparov) can force a draw by [[perpetual check]]. His friends told him so the next morning.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=146 | title=Garry Kasparov vs. Deep Blue | publisher=Chessbase.com | author=Frederic Friedel | work=Daily Chess Columns | accessdate=2007-04-20 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070409200142/http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=146 | archive-date=2007-04-09 | url-status=dead }}</ref> They suggested 47.h4 h5{{chesspunc|!}}, a position after which the black queen can perpetually check White. This is possible as Deep Blue moved 44.Kf1 instead of an alternate move of its king. Regarding the end of game 2 and 44.Kf1 in particular, chess journalist [[Mig Greengard]] in the ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine|Game Over]]'' film states, \"It turns out, that the position in, here at the end is actually a draw, and that, one of Deep Blue's final moves was a terrible error, because Deep Blue has two choices here. It can move its king here or move its king over here. It picked the wrong place to step.\" Another person in that film, four-time US champion [[Yasser Seirawan]], then concludes that \"The computer had left its king a little un-defended. And Garry could have threatened a perpetual check, not a win but a perpetual check.\"\n\nModern chess engines consider the final position as better (but maybe not won) for White.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://analysis.cpuchess.com/?fen=1r6%2F5kp1%2FRqQb1p1p%2F1p1PpP2%2F1Pp1B3%2F2P4P%2F6P1%2F5K2%20b%20-%20-%2014%2045&lmove=Ra6 | title=Online computer analysis of the final position of game 2 | accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chess.com/blog/FirebrandX/kasparov---deep-blue-1997-everyone-was-wrong | title=Kasparov \u2013 Deep Blue 1997: History gets it wrong! | accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref> The mistake was actually not 44.Kf1 but 45.Ra6{{chesspunc|?!}} when instead 45.Qd7+ was a clear win (White will exchange queens, bring his king to e4 and his bishop to g6 after which Black sooner or later is in [[zugzwang]], and will be mated, or lose his b5-pawn, or the d5-pawn advances, opening roads for the white king).\n\nThe move that surprised Kasparov enough to allege cheating was 36.axb5! axb5 37.Be4! after which Black is lost. A more {{chessgloss|materialism|materialistic}} machine could have won two pawns with 36.Qb6 Rd8 37.axb5 Rab8 38.Qxa6, but after 38...e4! Black would have acquired strong {{chessgloss|counterplay}}.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/deep-blue-s-cheating-move |title=Deep Blue's cheating move |last=Silver |first=Albert |date=2015-02-19 |work=Chess News |language=en-US}}</ref> Kasparov and many others thought the move 36.axb5! was too sophisticated for a computer, suggesting there had been some sort of human intervention during the game.\n\n===Game 3 {{anchor|1997 Game 3}}===\n''May 6''. The third game was interesting because Kasparov chose to use an [[irregular chess openings|irregular opening]], the [[Mieses Opening]]. He believed that by playing an esoteric opening, the computer would get out of its [[opening book]] and play the opening worse than it would have done using the book. Although this is nowadays a common tactic, it was a relatively new idea at the time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=149 | title=Mig on Chess #178: All the News That's Fit to Mock | publisher=Chessbase.com | work=Daily Chess Columns | accessdate=2007-04-19}}</ref> Despite this anti-computer tactic, the game was drawn.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.d3 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c4 Nf6 4.a3 d6 5.Nc3 Be7 6.g3 0-0 7.Bg2 Be6 8.0-0 Qd7 9.Ng5 Bf5 10.e4 Bg4 11.f3 Bh5 12.Nh3 Nd4 13.Nf2 h6 14.Be3 c5 15.b4 b6 16.Rb1 Kh8 17.Rb2 a6 18.bxc5 bxc5 19.Bh3 Qc7 20.Bg4 Bg6 21.f4 exf4 22.gxf4 Qa5 23.Bd2 Qxa3 24.Ra2 Qb3 25.f5 Qxd1 26.Bxd1 Bh7 27.Nh3 Rfb8 28.Nf4 Bd8 29.Nfd5 Nc6 30.Bf4 Ne5 31.Ba4 Nxd5 32.Nxd5 a5 33.Bb5 Ra7 34.Kg2 g5 35.Bxe5+ dxe5 36.f6 Bg6 37.h4 gxh4 38.Kh3 Kg8 39.Kxh4 Kh7 40.Kg4 Bc7 41.Nxc7 Rxc7 42.Rxa5 Rd8 43.Rf3 Kh8 44.Kh4 Kg8 45.Ra3 Kh8 46.Ra6 Kh7 47.Ra3 Kh8 48.Ra6 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 4 {{anchor|1997 Game 4}}===\n''May 7''. In this game Kasparov played the [[Caro\u2013Kann Defence]]. Kasparov got into time trouble late in the game.  The sub-optimal moves he played in a hurry may have cost him the victory.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game4/html/c.2.shtml | title=The official site of the matches \u2013 The 1997 game 4 | publisher=IBM Research | work=Deep Blue | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c6 2.d4 d6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 Bg4 5.h3 Bh5 6.Bd3 e6 7.Qe2 d5 8.Bg5 Be7 9.e5 Nfd7 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 11.g4 Bg6 12.Bxg6 hxg6 13.h4 Na6 14.0-0-0 0-0-0 15.Rdg1 Nc7 16.Kb1 f6 17.exf6 Qxf6 18.Rg3 Rde8 19.Re1 Rhf8 20.Nd1 e5 21.dxe5 Qf4 22.a3 Ne6 23.Nc3 Ndc5 24.b4 Nd7 25.Qd3 Qf7 26.b5 Ndc5 27.Qe3 Qf4 28.bxc6 bxc6 29.Rd1 Kc7 30.Ka1 Qxe3 31.fxe3 Rf7 32.Rh3 Ref8 33.Nd4 Rf2 34.Rb1 Rg2 35.Nce2 Rxg4 36.Nxe6+ Nxe6 37.Nd4 Nxd4 38.exd4 Rxd4 39.Rg1 Rc4 40.Rxg6 Rxc2 41.Rxg7+ Kb6 42.Rb3+ Kc5 43.Rxa7 Rf1+ 44.Rb1 Rff2 45.Rb4 Rc1+ 46.Rb1 Rcc2 47.Rb4 Rc1+ 48.Rb1 Rxb1+ 49.Kxb1 Re2 50.Re7 Rh2 51.Rh7 Kc4 52.Rc7 c5 53.e6 Rxh4 54.e7 Re4 55.a4 Kb3 56.Kc1 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 5 {{anchor|1997 Game 5}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1997, rd 5''' \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |pd|pd|  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |kd|pd|  |  |nl|  | \n |  |nd|  |  |rl|  |pl| \n |  |  |  |rd|  |  |  | \n |  |kl|  |  |  |  |  | \n |Final position after 49...Kb4\n}}\n''May 10''. In this game, the [[King's Indian Attack]] opening was played. As in the previous game, Deep Blue played a brilliant [[Chess endgame|endgame]] that secured a draw, when it was looking as if Kasparov would win. It was later discovered that Kasparov had a win beginning with 44.Rg7+.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/komodo-8-deep-blue-revisited-part-three |title=\nKomodo 8: Deep Blue revisited (part three) |publisher=[[ChessBase]] |access-date=29 June 2019 |date=9 January 2015 |last=Silver |first=Albert }}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 Nd7 4.h3 Bxf3 5.Bxf3 c6 6.d3 e6 7.e4 Ne5 8.Bg2 dxe4 9.Bxe4 Nf6 10.Bg2 Bb4+ 11.Nd2 h5 12.Qe2 Qc7 13.c3 Be7 14.d4 Ng6 15.h4 e5 16.Nf3 exd4 17.Nxd4 0-0-0 18.Bg5 Ng4 19.0-0-0 Rhe8 20.Qc2 Kb8 21.Kb1 Bxg5 22.hxg5 N6e5 23.Rhe1 c5 24.Nf3 Rxd1+ 25.Rxd1 Nc4 26.Qa4 Rd8 27.Re1 Nb6 28.Qc2 Qd6 29.c4 Qg6 30.Qxg6 fxg6 31.b3 Nxf2 32.Re6 Kc7 33.Rxg6 Rd7 34.Nh4 Nc8 35.Bd5 Nd6 36.Re6 Nb5 37.cxb5 Rxd5 38.Rg6 Rd7 39.Nf5 Ne4 40.Nxg7 Rd1+ 41.Kc2 Rd2+ 42.Kc1 Rxa2 43.Nxh5 Nd2 44.Nf4 Nxb3+ 45.Kb1 Rd2 46.Re6 c4 47.Re3 Kb6 48.g6 Kxb5 49.g7 Kb4 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\nIf White plays 50.g8=Q then Black can force a draw by threefold repetition, starting with 50...Rd1+ and then 51...Rd2+.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Game 6 {{anchor|1997 Game 6}}===\n{{main article|Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6}}\n{{Chess diagram   \n|tright\n| '''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1997, rd 6''' \n|rd|  |bd|qd|kd|bd|  |rd\n|pd|pd|  |nd|  |pd|pd| \n|  |  |pd|  |pd|nd|  |pd\n|  |  |  |  |  |  |nl| \n|  |  |  |pl|  |  |  | \n|  |  |  |bl|  |nl|  | \n|pl|pl|pl|  |  |pl|pl|pl\n|rl|  |bl|ql|kl|  |  |rl\n|Position after 7...h6\n}}\n''May 11''. Before the sixth game, the overall score was even: 2\u00bd\u20132\u00bd. As in game 4, Kasparov played the [[Caro\u2013Kann Defence]]. Deep Blue made a knight [[sacrifice (chess)|sacrifice]] which wrecked Kasparov's defence and forced him to resign in less than twenty moves. As Kasparov later recounts, he chose to play a dubious opening in an effort to put Deep Blue out of its comfort zone. Although the knight sacrifice is a well known refutation, Kasparov reasoned that an engine wouldn't play the move without a concrete gain. The only reason Deep Blue played in that way, as was later revealed, was because that very same day of the game the creators of Deep Blue had inputted the variation into the opening database.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nd7 5.Ng5 Ngf6 6.Bd3 e6 7.N1f3 h6 (''diagram'') 8.Nxe6 Qe7 9.0-0 fxe6 10.Bg6+ Kd8 11.Bf4 b5 12.a4 Bb7 13.Re1 Nd5 14.Bg3 Kc8 15.axb5 cxb5 16.Qd3 Bc6 17.Bf5 exf5 18.Rxe7 Bxe7 19.c4 1\u20130}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[AlphaGo versus Lee Sedol]], similar but with Go\n* [[Arimaa]]&nbsp;\u2013 Kasparov's loss to Deep Blue inspired the creation of a new game designed to be difficult for computers, yet playable with a chess set.\n* ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]''\n* [[List of chess games]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/ | title=The official site of the matches | publisher=IBM Research | work=Deep Blue | accessdate=2007-04-17}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?pid=29912&pid2=15940 | website=[[Chessgames.com]] | title=Garry Kasparov vs Deep Blue, 12 games | accessdate=2007-04-18}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Gardner|first=Martin|authorlink=Martin Gardner\n|year=2001\n|title=A Gardner's Workout: Training the Mind and Entertaining the Spirit\n|publisher=A K Peters\n|isbn=978-1-56881-120-8\n|pages=91\u201395}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last1=Goodman|first1=David\n|last2=Keene|first2=Raymond|authorlink2=Raymond Keene\n|year=1997\n|title=Man Versus Machine: Kasparov Versus Deep Blue\n|publisher=H3\n|isbn=978-1888281064}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Hsu|first=Feng-hsiung|authorlink=Feng-hsiung Hsu\n|year=2002\n|title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the World Chess Champion\n|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]\n|isbn=0-691-09065-3\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last1=Khodarkovsky|first1=Michael\n|last2=Shamkovich|first2=Leonoid|authorlink2=Leonid Shamkovich\n|year=1997\n|title=A New Era: World Championship Chess in the Age of Deep Blue\n|publisher=Ballantine\n|isbn=978-0345408907}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=King|first=Daniel|authorlink=Daniel King (chess player)\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov v. Deeper Blue: The Ultimate Man v. Machine Challenge\n|publisher=Batsford\n|isbn=0-7134-8322-9\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Newborn|first=Monty|authorlink=Monty Newborn\n|year=1996\n|title=Kasparov versus Deep Blue: Computer Chess Comes of Age\n|publisher=Springer\n|isbn=0-387-94820-1\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Pandolfini|first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Pandolfini\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov and Deep Blue: The Historic Chess Match Between Man and Machine\n|publisher=Fireside Chess Library\n|isbn=9780684848525\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov}}\n[[Category:Chess competitions]]\n[[Category:Computer chess]]\n[[Category:Chess in the United States]]\n[[Category:1996 in chess]]\n[[Category:1997 in chess]]\n[[Category:Chess rivalries]]\n[[Category:History of chess]]\n[[Category:1996 in sports in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1997 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1996 in American sports]]\n[[Category:1997 in American sports]]\n[[Category:IBM]]\n[[Category:Human versus computer matches]]\n[[Category:1996 in computer science]]\n[[Category:1997 in computer science]]\n[[Category:Sports in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chess matches between Deep Blue and Kasparov}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = [[File:Chess klt45.svg|30px]] Deep Blue vs. Kasparov\n| header_align = center\n| header_background = \n| footer = '''First match'''\n* February 10, 1996: took place in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n* Result: '''Kasparov'''\u2013Deep Blue (4\u20132)\n* Record set: First computer program to defeat a world champion in a ''{{chessgloss|classical}} game'' under tournament regulations\n\n'''Second match (rematch)'''\n* May 11, 1997: held in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Result: '''Deep Blue'''\u2013Kasparov (3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd)\n* Record set: First computer program to defeat a world champion in a ''match'' under tournament regulations\n| footer_align = left\n| footer_background = \n| width = \n| image1 = Deep Blue.jpg\n| width1 = 160\n| caption1 = [[Deep Blue (chess computer)|Deep Blue]] <br /><small>[[IBM]] [[Computer chess|chess computer]]</small>\n| image2 = Kasparov-29.jpg\n| width2 = 160\n| caption2 = [[Garry Kasparov]] <br /><small>[[World Chess Champion]]</small>\n| caption_align = center\n}}\n\n'''Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov''' was a pair of six-game [[chess]] matches between world chess champion [[Garry Kasparov]] and an IBM supercomputer called [[Deep Blue (chess computer)|Deep Blue]].  The first match was played in Philadelphia in 1996 and won by Kasparov.   The second was played in New York City in 1997 and won by Deep Blue.  The 1997 match was the first defeat of a reigning world chess champion by a computer under tournament conditions.\n\nThe 1997 match was the subject of a documentary film, ''The Man vs. The Machine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=11694550 |title=Signals: The Man vs. The Machine |last1= |website=espn.go.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=2014-10-24}}</ref>\n{{algebraic notation|pos=toc}}\n\n==Symbolic significance==\nDeep Blue's win was seen as symbolically significant, a sign that artificial intelligence was catching up to human intelligence, and could defeat one of humanity's great intellectual champions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Be Afraid|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/be-afraid/article/9802|publisher=www.weeklystandard.com|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=26 May 1997}}</ref> Later analysis tended to play down Kasparov's loss as a result of uncharacteristically bad play on Kasparov's part, and play down the intellectual value of chess as a game that can be defeated by brute force.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Somers|first1=James|title=The Man Who Would Teach Machines to Think|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2013/11/the-man-who-would-teach-machines-to-think/309529/|accessdate=28 September 2016|publisher=www.theatlantic.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Finley|first1=Klint|title=Did a Computer Bug Help Deep Blue Beat Kasparov?|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/09/deep-blue-computer-bug/|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, discussing the match in a podcast with neuroscientist Sam Harris, Kasparov advised of a change of heart in his views of this match. Kasparov stated: \"While writing the book I did a lot of research \u2013 analysing the games with modern computers, also soul-searching \u2013 and I changed my conclusions. I am not writing any love letters to IBM, but my respect for the Deep Blue team went up, and my opinion of my own play, and Deep Blue's play, went down. Today you can buy a chess engine for your laptop that will beat Deep Blue quite easily.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/kasparov-on-the-future-of-artificial-intelligence|title=Kasparov on the future of Artificial Intelligence|date=2016-12-29|newspaper=Chess News|access-date=2016-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDeep Blue's victory switched the canonical example of a game where humans outmatched machines to the ancient Chinese game of [[Go (game)|Go]], a game of simple rules and far more possible moves than chess, which requires more intuition and is less susceptible to brute force.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Electronic Holy War|url=http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/the-electronic-holy-war|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=25 March 2014}}</ref> Go is widely played in China, South Korea, and Japan, and was considered one of the [[four arts of the Chinese scholar]] in antiquity. [[Go programs]] were able to defeat only amateur players until 2015, when Google DeepMind's [[AlphaGo]] program surprisingly defeated [[Lee Sedol]] in the match [[AlphaGo versus Lee Sedol]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Byford|first1=Sam|title=DeepMind's AlphaGo secures victory over Lee Se-dol with third straight win|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/12/11210650/alphago-deepmind-go-match-3-result|website=The Verge|accessdate=28 September 2016|date=12 March 2016}}</ref> While Deep Blue mainly relied on brute computational force to evaluate millions of positions, AlphaGo also relied on [[neural network]]s and [[reinforcement learning]].\n\n==Summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=left\n|+ The 1996 match\n|-\n!Game #\n!White\n!Black\n!Result\n!Comment\n|-\n| 1 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130||\n|-\n| 2 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n| 3 || Deep Blue || Kasparov || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || [[Draw by agreement|Draw by mutual agreement]]\n|-\n| 4 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n| 5 || Deep Blue || '''Kasparov''' || 0\u20131 || Kasparov offered a draw after the 23rd move.\n|-\n| 6 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | ''Result:'' Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue: 4\u20132\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=left\n|+The 1997 rematch\n|-\n!Game #\n!White\n!Black\n!Result\n!Comment\n|-\n|1 || '''Kasparov''' || Deep Blue || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n|2 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n|3 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|4 || Deep Blue || Kasparov || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|5 || Kasparov || Deep Blue || \u00bd\u2013\u00bd || Draw by mutual agreement\n|-\n|6 || '''Deep Blue''' || Kasparov || 1\u20130 ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | ''Result:'' Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov: 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==1996 match==\n\n===Game 1 {{anchor|1996 Game 1}}===\n{{main article|Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1}}\n{{Chess diagram \n |tright\n |'''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1996, rd 1'''\n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |rl\n |  |  |  |  |  |qd|  |kd\n |  |  |  |ql|  |  |nl|  \n |  |  |  |pd|  |  |  |  \n |pl|pl|  |  |  |pd|pl|pl\n |  |  |  |  |  |nd|  |kl\n |  |  |  |  |rd|  |  |  \n |Final position after 37.Rxh7{{chessAN|+}}\n}}\n''February 10''. The first game of the 1996 match was the first game to be won by a [[Computer chess|chess-playing computer]] against a reigning [[World Chess Championship|world champion]] under normal chess tournament conditions, and in particular, {{chessgloss|classical}} [[time control]]s.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c5 2.c3 d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.Be2 e6 7.h3 Bh5 8.0-0 Nc6 9.Be3 cxd4 10.cxd4 Bb4 11.a3 Ba5 12.Nc3 Qd6 13.Nb5 Qe7 14.Ne5 Bxe2 15.Qxe2 0-0 16.Rac1 Rac8 17.Bg5 Bb6 18.Bxf6 gxf6 19.Nc4 Rfd8 20.Nxb6 axb6 21.Rfd1 f5 22.Qe3 Qf6 23.d5 Rxd5 24.Rxd5 exd5 25.b3 Kh8 26.Qxb6 Rg8 27.Qc5 d4 28.Nd6 f4 29.Nxb7 Ne5 30.Qd5 f3 31.g3 Nd3 32.Rc7 Re8 33.Nd6 Re1+ 34.Kh2 Nxf2 35.Nxf7+ Kg7 36.Ng5+ Kh6 37.Rxh7+ {{chessAN|1\u20130}}}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Game 2 {{anchor|1996 Game 2}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n |'''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1996, rd 2''' \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |kd|  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |bl|  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |pd|  |pl|  |pl\n |  |  |  |  |bd|  |pl|  \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  \n |  |  |  |  |  |kl|  |  \n |Final position after 73.Bb5\n}}\n''February 11''. The second game began with the Open [[Catalan Opening]]. Kasparov played in what could be called a preemptive style blocking all Deep Blue's {{chessgloss|development}} attempts. The game lasted for 73 moves but eventually Deep Blue's operator had to [[Resignation|resign]] the game for the computer in a position where both players had a bishop but Kasparov had three pawns to Deep Blue's one.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 e6 3.g3 c5 4.Bg2 Nc6 5.0-0 Nf6 6.c4 dxc4 7.Ne5 Bd7 8.Na3 cxd4 9.Naxc4 Bc5 10.Qb3 0-0 11.Qxb7 Nxe5 12.Nxe5 Rb8 13.Qf3 Bd6 14.Nc6 Bxc6 15.Qxc6 e5 16.Rb1 Rb6 17.Qa4 Qb8 18.Bg5 Be7 19.b4 Bxb4 20.Bxf6 gxf6 21.Qd7 Qc8 22.Qxa7 Rb8 23.Qa4 Bc3 24.Rxb8 Qxb8 25.Be4 Qc7 26.Qa6 Kg7 27.Qd3 Rb8 28.Bxh7 Rb2 29.Be4 Rxa2 30.h4 Qc8 31.Qf3 Ra1 32.Rxa1 Bxa1 33.Qh5 Qh8 34.Qg4+ Kf8 35.Qc8+ Kg7 36.Qg4+ Kf8 37.Bd5 Ke7 38.Bc6 Kf8 39.Bd5 Ke7 40.Qf3 Bc3 41.Bc4 Qc8 42.Qd5 Qe6 43.Qb5 Qd7 44.Qc5+ Qd6 45.Qa7+ Qd7 46.Qa8 Qc7 47.Qa3+ Qd6 48.Qa2 f5 49.Bxf7 e4 50.Bh5 Qf6 51.Qa3+ Kd7 52.Qa7+ Kd8 53.Qb8+ Kd7 54.Be8+ Ke7 55.Bb5 Bd2 56.Qc7+ Kf8 57.Bc4 Bc3 58.Kg2 Be1 59.Kf1 Bc3 60.f4 exf3 61.exf3 Bd2 62.f4 Ke8 63.Qc8+ Ke7 64.Qc5+ Kd8 65.Bd3 Be3 66.Qxf5 Qc6 67.Qf8+ Kc7 68.Qe7+ Kc8 69.Bf5+ Kb8 70.Qd8+ Kb7 71.Qd7+ Qxd7 72.Bxd7 Kc7 73.Bb5 1\u20130}}\n\n===Game 3 {{anchor|1996 Game 3}}===\n''February 13''. In the third game Kasparov played the [[Sicilian Defence]] to which Deep Blue responded with the [[Sicilian Defence, Alapin Variation|Alapin Variation]]. The game lasted for 39 moves and was drawn.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c5 2.c3 d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.Be2 e6 7.0-0 Nc6 8.Be3 cxd4 9.cxd4 Bb4 10.a3 Ba5 11.Nc3 Qd6 12.Ne5 Bxe2 13.Qxe2 Bxc3 14.bxc3 Nxe5 15.Bf4 Nf3+ 16.Qxf3 Qd5 17.Qd3 Rc8 18.Rfc1 Qc4 19.Qxc4 Rxc4 20.Rcb1 b6 21.Bb8 Ra4 22.Rb4 Ra5 23.Rc4 0-0 24.Bd6 Ra8 25.Rc6 b5 26.Kf1 Ra4 27.Rb1 a6 28.Ke2 h5 29.Kd3 Rd8 30.Be7 Rd7 31.Bxf6 gxf6 32.Rb3 Kg7 33.Ke3 e5 34.g3 exd4+ 35.cxd4 Re7+ 36.Kf3 Rd7 37.Rd3 Raxd4 38.Rxd4 Rxd4 39.Rxa6 b4 {{chessAN|\u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}}}\n\n===Game 4 {{anchor|1996 Game 4}}===\n''February 14''. The fourth game was the second game to end in a draw, even though at one point Deep Blue's team refused Kasparov's [[Draw by agreement|draw offer]]. The opening played was the [[Semi-Slav Defense]].\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 c6 3.c4 e6 4.Nbd2 Nf6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 Bd6 7.e4 dxe4 8.Nxe4 Nxe4 9.Bxe4 0-0 10.0-0 h6 11.Bc2 e5 12.Re1 exd4 13.Qxd4 Bc5 14.Qc3 a5 15.a3 Nf6 16.Be3 Bxe3 17.Rxe3 Bg4 18.Ne5 Re8 19.Rae1 Be6 20.f4 Qc8 21.h3 b5 22.f5 Bxc4 23.Nxc4 bxc4 24.Rxe8+ Nxe8 25.Re4 Nf6 26.Rxc4 Nd5 27.Qe5 Qd7 28.Rg4 f6 29.Qd4 Kh7 30.Re4 Rd8 31.Kh1 Qc7 32.Qf2 Qb8 33.Ba4 c5 34.Bc6 c4 35.Rxc4 Nb4 36.Bf3 Nd3 37.Qh4 Qxb2 38.Qg3 Qxa3 39.Rc7 Qf8 40.Ra7 Ne5 41.Rxa5 Qf7 42.Rxe5 fxe5 43.Qxe5 Re8 44.Qf4 Qf6 45.Bh5 Rf8 46.Bg6+ Kh8 47.Qc7 Qd4 48.Kh2 Ra8 49.Bh5 Qf6 50.Bg6 Rg8 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 5 {{anchor|1996 Game 5}}===\n''February 16''. The fifth game was the turning point of the match. During the game, Kasparov, playing Black, chose a different opening, the [[Four Knights Game]], from the [[Sicilian Defence]] he had played in games one and three and came out on top. This game was particularly embarrassing for the Deep Blue team, because they had declined Kasparov's draw offer after the 23rd move. This was the only game in the match that Black won.\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Nc3 Nc6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bb4 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.exd5 cxd5 9.0-0 0-0 10.Bg5 c6 11.Qf3 Be7 12.Rae1 Re8 13.Ne2 h6 14.Bf4 Bd6 15.Nd4 Bg4 16.Qg3 Bxf4 17.Qxf4 Qb6 18.c4 Bd7 19.cxd5 cxd5 20.Rxe8+ Rxe8 21.Qd2 Ne4 22.Bxe4 dxe4 23.b3 Rd8 {{chessAN|({{=}})}} 24.Qc3 f5 25.Rd1 Be6 26.Qe3 Bf7 27.Qc3 f4 28.Rd2 Qf6 29.g3 Rd5 30.a3 Kh7 31.Kg2 Qe5 32.f3 e3 33.Rd3 e2 34.gxf4 e1=Q 35.fxe5 Qxc3 36.Rxc3 Rxd4 37.b4 Bc4 38.Kf2 g5 39.Re3 Be6 40.Rc3 Bc4 41.Re3 Rd2+ 42.Ke1 Rd3 43.Kf2 Kg6 44.Rxd3 Bxd3 45.Ke3 Bc2 46.Kd4 Kf5 47.Kd5 h5 {{chessAN|0\u20131}}}}\n\n===Game 6 {{anchor|1996 Game 6}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1996, rd 6''' \n |rd|bd|rd|  |  |  |  | \n |  |qd|  |  |  |pd|  | \n |pd|pl|pd|  |pd|bl|pd|kd\n |pl|  |ql|pd|pl|  |  |pd\n |  |rl|  |  |  |  |  |pl\n |  |  |  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |pl|  | \n |  |  |rl|  |  |  |kl| \n |Final position after 43.Rb4\n}}\n''February 17''. The sixth game was an illustration of just how badly chess engines could play in some positions at the time. Employing anti-computer tactics and keeping the focus of the game on long-term planning, Kasparov slowly improved his position throughout the mid-game while Deep Blue wasted time doing very little to improve its position. By the end of the game, Deep Blue's pieces were crammed into its queenside corner, with no moves to make aside from shuffling its king. Kasparov had all the time in the world to finish the rout.<ref>{{Citation |last=Burgess |first=Graham |authorlink=Graham Burgess |title=The Mammoth Book of Chess |year=2010 |edition= |publisher=Running Press |id= |pages=}}</ref> Kasparov's next move would probably have been 44.Qe7 to exchange the queens. That would have allowed his pawn, which was about to [[promotion (chess)|promote]], to advance.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.chesscafe.com/text/kibitz91.pdf | title=How Much Longer Can Man Match the Computer? | publisher=Chesscafe.com | author=Tim Harding | work=The Kibitzer | accessdate=2008-02-09 |format = 118 [[kilobyte|kB]] [[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 c6 3.c4 e6 4.Nbd2 Nf6 5.e3 c5 6.b3 Nc6 7.Bb2 cxd4 8.exd4 Be7 9.Rc1 0-0 10.Bd3 Bd7 11.0-0 Nh5 12.Re1 Nf4 13.Bb1 Bd6 14.g3 Ng6 15.Ne5 Rc8 16.Nxd7 Qxd7 17.Nf3 Bb4 18.Re3 Rfd8 19.h4 Nge7 20.a3 Ba5 21.b4 Bc7 22.c5 Re8 23.Qd3 g6 24.Re2 Nf5 25.Bc3 h5 26.b5 Nce7 27.Bd2 Kg7 28.a4 Ra8 29.a5 a6 30.b6 Bb8 31.Bc2 Nc6 32.Ba4 Re7 33.Bc3 Ne5 34.dxe5 Qxa4 35.Nd4 Nxd4 36.Qxd4 Qd7 37.Bd2 Re8 38.Bg5 Rc8 39.Bf6+ Kh7 40.c6 bxc6 41.Qc5 Kh6 42.Rb2 Qb7 43.Rb4 1\u20130}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==1997 rematch==\n\n===Game 1 {{anchor|1997 Game 1}}===\n''May 3''. The 1997 rematch began with the [[King's Indian Attack]], which led Kasparov to victory in 45 moves.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.b3 Nd7 4.Bb2 e6 5.Bg2 Ngf6 6.0-0 c6 7.d3 Bd6 8.Nbd2 0-0 9.h3 Bh5 10.e3 h6 11.Qe1 Qa5 12.a3 Bc7 13.Nh4 g5 14.Nhf3 e5 15.e4 Rfe8 16.Nh2 Qb6 17.Qc1 a5 18.Re1 Bd6 19.Ndf1 dxe4 20.dxe4 Bc5 21.Ne3 Rad8 22.Nhf1 g4 23.hxg4 Nxg4 24.f3 Nxe3 25.Nxe3 Be7 26.Kh1 Bg5 27.Re2 a4 28.b4 f5 29.exf5 e4 30.f4 Bxe2 31.fxg5 Ne5 32.g6 Bf3 33.Bc3 Qb5 34.Qf1 Qxf1+ 35.Rxf1 h5 36.Kg1 Kf8 37.Bh3 b5 38.Kf2 Kg7 39.g4 Kh6 40.Rg1 hxg4 41.Bxg4 Bxg4 42.Nxg4+ Nxg4+ 43.Rxg4 Rd5 44.f6 Rd1 45.g7 1\u20130}}\n\nDeep Blue's 44th move in this game was allegedly the result of a [[bug (software)|bug]] in which Deep Blue, unable to determine a desirable move, resorted to a fail-safe.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.cnet.com/news/did-a-bug-in-deep-blue-lead-to-kasparovs-defeat/ | title=Did a bug in Deep Blue lead to Kasparov's defeat? | publisher=cnet.com | author=Tim Hornyak | accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> [[Nate Silver]] proposes that Kasparov \"concluded that the counterintuitive play must be a sign of superior intelligence\", leading him to lose the second game.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|title=Thinking Machines: The Search for Artificial Intelligence|journal=Distillations |date=2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=14\u201323|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>Silver, Nate. ''[[The Signal and the Noise|The Signal and the Noise: Why so Many Predictions Fail\u2014but Some Don't]].'' New York: Penguin, 2012. Print.</ref>\n\n===Game 2 {{anchor|1997 Game 2}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1997, rd 2''' \n |  |rd|  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |  |  |  |  |kd|pd| \n |rl|qd|ql|bd|  |pd|  |pd\n |  |pd|  |pl|pd|pl|  |\n |  |pl|pd|  |bl|  |  |\n |  |  |pl|  |  |  |  |pl \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |kl|  | \n |Final position after 45.Ra6\n}}\n''May 4.'' The game started with the [[Ruy Lopez]] opening, [[Ruy Lopez#Smyslov Variation|Smyslov Variation]]. Kasparov eventually resigned, although post-game analysis indicates that he could have held a draw in the final position. After this game Kasparov accused IBM of cheating, by alleging that a grandmaster (presumably a top rival) had been behind a certain move. The claim was repeated in the documentary ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117921798.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine|author=Robert Koehler|date=2003-09-09|publisher=Variety|accessdate=2008-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/deep-blue-s-cheating-move|title=Deep Blue's cheating move|date=2015-02-19|website=Chess News|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-28}}</ref> \n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.0-0 Be7 6.Re1 b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 0-0 9.h3 h6 10.d4 Re8 11.Nbd2 Bf8 12.Nf1 Bd7 13.Ng3 Na5 14.Bc2 c5 15.b3 Nc6 16.d5 Ne7 17.Be3 Ng6 18.Qd2 Nh7 19.a4 Nh4 20.Nxh4 Qxh4 21.Qe2 Qd8 22.b4 Qc7 23.Rec1 c4 24.Ra3 Rec8 25.Rca1 Qd8 26.f4 Nf6 27.fxe5 dxe5 28.Qf1 Ne8 29.Qf2 Nd6 30.Bb6 Qe8 31.R3a2 Be7 32.Bc5 Bf8 33.Nf5 Bxf5 34.exf5 f6 35.Bxd6 Bxd6 36.axb5 axb5 37.Be4 Rxa2 38.Qxa2 Qd7 39.Qa7 Rc7 40.Qb6 Rb7 41.Ra8+ Kf7 42.Qa6 Qc7 43.Qc6 Qb6+ 44.Kf1 Rb8 45.Ra6 1\u20130}}\n\nAt the time it was reported that Kasparov missed the fact that after 45...Qe3 46.Qxd6 Re8, Black (Kasparov) can force a draw by [[perpetual check]]. His friends told him so the next morning.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=146 | title=Garry Kasparov vs. Deep Blue | publisher=Chessbase.com | author=Frederic Friedel | work=Daily Chess Columns | accessdate=2007-04-20 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070409200142/http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=146 | archive-date=2007-04-09 | url-status=dead }}</ref> They suggested 47.h4 h5{{chesspunc|!}}, a position after which the black queen can perpetually check White. This is possible as Deep Blue moved 44.Kf1 instead of an alternate move of its king. Regarding the end of game 2 and 44.Kf1 in particular, chess journalist [[Mig Greengard]] in the ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine|Game Over]]'' film states, \"It turns out, that the position in, here at the end is actually a draw, and that, one of Deep Blue's final moves was a terrible error, because Deep Blue has two choices here. It can move its king here or move its king over here. It picked the wrong place to step.\" Another person in that film, four-time US champion [[Yasser Seirawan]], then concludes that, \"The computer had left its king a little un-defended. And Garry could have threatened a perpetual check, not a win but a perpetual check.\"\n\nModern chess engines consider the final position as better (but maybe not won) for White.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://analysis.cpuchess.com/?fen=1r6%2F5kp1%2FRqQb1p1p%2F1p1PpP2%2F1Pp1B3%2F2P4P%2F6P1%2F5K2%20b%20-%20-%2014%2045&lmove=Ra6 | title=Online computer analysis of the final position of game 2 | accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chess.com/blog/FirebrandX/kasparov---deep-blue-1997-everyone-was-wrong | title=Kasparov \u2013 Deep Blue 1997: History gets it wrong! | accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref> The mistake was actually not 44.Kf1 but 45.Ra6{{chesspunc|?!}} when instead 45.Qd7+ was a clear win (White will exchange queens, bring his king to e4 and his bishop to g6 after which Black sooner or later is in [[zugzwang]], and will be mated, or lose his b5-pawn, or the d5-pawn advances, opening roads for the white king).\n\nThe move that surprised Kasparov enough to allege cheating was 36.axb5! axb5 37.Be4! after which Black is lost. A more {{chessgloss|materialism|materialistic}} machine could have won two pawns with 36.Qb6 Rd8 37.axb5 Rab8 38.Qxa6, but after 38...e4! Black would have acquired strong {{chessgloss|counterplay}}.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/deep-blue-s-cheating-move |title=Deep Blue's cheating move |last=Silver |first=Albert |date=2015-02-19 |work=Chess News |language=en-US}}</ref> Kasparov and many others thought the move 36.axb5! was too sophisticated for a computer, suggesting there had been some sort of human intervention during the game.\n\n===Game 3 {{anchor|1997 Game 3}}===\n''May 6''. The third game was interesting because Kasparov chose to use an [[irregular chess openings|irregular opening]], the [[Mieses Opening]]. He believed that by playing an esoteric opening, the computer would get out of its [[opening book]] and play the opening worse than it would have done using the book. Although this is nowadays a common tactic, it was a relatively new idea at the time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chessbase.com/columns/column.asp?pid=149 | title=Mig on Chess #178: All the News That's Fit to Mock | publisher=Chessbase.com | work=Daily Chess Columns | accessdate=2007-04-19}}</ref> Despite this anti-computer tactic, the game was drawn.\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.d3 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c4 Nf6 4.a3 d6 5.Nc3 Be7 6.g3 0-0 7.Bg2 Be6 8.0-0 Qd7 9.Ng5 Bf5 10.e4 Bg4 11.f3 Bh5 12.Nh3 Nd4 13.Nf2 h6 14.Be3 c5 15.b4 b6 16.Rb1 Kh8 17.Rb2 a6 18.bxc5 bxc5 19.Bh3 Qc7 20.Bg4 Bg6 21.f4 exf4 22.gxf4 Qa5 23.Bd2 Qxa3 24.Ra2 Qb3 25.f5 Qxd1 26.Bxd1 Bh7 27.Nh3 Rfb8 28.Nf4 Bd8 29.Nfd5 Nc6 30.Bf4 Ne5 31.Ba4 Nxd5 32.Nxd5 a5 33.Bb5 Ra7 34.Kg2 g5 35.Bxe5+ dxe5 36.f6 Bg6 37.h4 gxh4 38.Kh3 Kg8 39.Kxh4 Kh7 40.Kg4 Bc7 41.Nxc7 Rxc7 42.Rxa5 Rd8 43.Rf3 Kh8 44.Kh4 Kg8 45.Ra3 Kh8 46.Ra6 Kh7 47.Ra3 Kh8 48.Ra6 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 4 {{anchor|1997 Game 4}}===\n''May 7''. In this game Kasparov played the [[Caro\u2013Kann Defence]]. Kasparov got into time trouble late in the game.  The sub-optimal moves he played in a hurry may have cost him the victory.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game4/html/c.2.shtml | title=The official site of the matches \u2013 The 1997 game 4 | publisher=IBM Research | work=Deep Blue | accessdate=2007-04-20}}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c6 2.d4 d6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 Bg4 5.h3 Bh5 6.Bd3 e6 7.Qe2 d5 8.Bg5 Be7 9.e5 Nfd7 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 11.g4 Bg6 12.Bxg6 hxg6 13.h4 Na6 14.0-0-0 0-0-0 15.Rdg1 Nc7 16.Kb1 f6 17.exf6 Qxf6 18.Rg3 Rde8 19.Re1 Rhf8 20.Nd1 e5 21.dxe5 Qf4 22.a3 Ne6 23.Nc3 Ndc5 24.b4 Nd7 25.Qd3 Qf7 26.b5 Ndc5 27.Qe3 Qf4 28.bxc6 bxc6 29.Rd1 Kc7 30.Ka1 Qxe3 31.fxe3 Rf7 32.Rh3 Ref8 33.Nd4 Rf2 34.Rb1 Rg2 35.Nce2 Rxg4 36.Nxe6+ Nxe6 37.Nd4 Nxd4 38.exd4 Rxd4 39.Rg1 Rc4 40.Rxg6 Rxc2 41.Rxg7+ Kb6 42.Rb3+ Kc5 43.Rxa7 Rf1+ 44.Rb1 Rff2 45.Rb4 Rc1+ 46.Rb1 Rcc2 47.Rb4 Rc1+ 48.Rb1 Rxb1+ 49.Kxb1 Re2 50.Re7 Rh2 51.Rh7 Kc4 52.Rc7 c5 53.e6 Rxh4 54.e7 Re4 55.a4 Kb3 56.Kc1 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\n===Game 5 {{anchor|1997 Game 5}}===\n{{Chess diagram  \n |tright\n | '''Kasparov\u2013Deep Blue, 1997, rd 5''' \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |pd|pd|  |  |  |  |pl| \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |  |  |  |  |  |  | \n |  |kd|pd|  |  |nl|  | \n |  |nd|  |  |rl|  |pl| \n |  |  |  |rd|  |  |  | \n |  |kl|  |  |  |  |  | \n |Final position after 49...Kb4\n}}\n''May 10''. In this game, the [[King's Indian Attack]] opening was played. As in the previous game, Deep Blue played a brilliant [[Chess endgame|endgame]] that secured a draw, when it was looking as if Kasparov would win. It was later discovered that Kasparov had a win beginning with 44.Rg7+.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/komodo-8-deep-blue-revisited-part-three |title=\nKomodo 8: Deep Blue revisited (part three) |publisher=[[ChessBase]] |access-date=29 June 2019 |date=9 January 2015 |last=Silver |first=Albert }}</ref>\n\n{{block indent |1=Kasparov vs. Deep Blue <br />1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 Nd7 4.h3 Bxf3 5.Bxf3 c6 6.d3 e6 7.e4 Ne5 8.Bg2 dxe4 9.Bxe4 Nf6 10.Bg2 Bb4+ 11.Nd2 h5 12.Qe2 Qc7 13.c3 Be7 14.d4 Ng6 15.h4 e5 16.Nf3 exd4 17.Nxd4 0-0-0 18.Bg5 Ng4 19.0-0-0 Rhe8 20.Qc2 Kb8 21.Kb1 Bxg5 22.hxg5 N6e5 23.Rhe1 c5 24.Nf3 Rxd1+ 25.Rxd1 Nc4 26.Qa4 Rd8 27.Re1 Nb6 28.Qc2 Qd6 29.c4 Qg6 30.Qxg6 fxg6 31.b3 Nxf2 32.Re6 Kc7 33.Rxg6 Rd7 34.Nh4 Nc8 35.Bd5 Nd6 36.Re6 Nb5 37.cxb5 Rxd5 38.Rg6 Rd7 39.Nf5 Ne4 40.Nxg7 Rd1+ 41.Kc2 Rd2+ 42.Kc1 Rxa2 43.Nxh5 Nd2 44.Nf4 Nxb3+ 45.Kb1 Rd2 46.Re6 c4 47.Re3 Kb6 48.g6 Kxb5 49.g7 Kb4 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd}}\n\nIf White plays 50.g8=Q then Black can force a draw by threefold repetition, starting with 50...Rd1+ and then 51...Rd2+.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Game 6 {{anchor|1997 Game 6}}===\n{{main article|Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6}}\n{{Chess diagram   \n|tright\n| '''Deep Blue\u2013Kasparov, 1997, rd 6''' \n|rd|  |bd|qd|kd|bd|  |rd\n|pd|pd|  |nd|  |pd|pd| \n|  |  |pd|  |pd|nd|  |pd\n|  |  |  |  |  |  |nl| \n|  |  |  |pl|  |  |  | \n|  |  |  |bl|  |nl|  | \n|pl|pl|pl|  |  |pl|pl|pl\n|rl|  |bl|ql|kl|  |  |rl\n|Position after 7...h6\n}}\n''May 11''. Before the sixth game, the overall score was even: 2\u00bd\u20132\u00bd. As in game 4, Kasparov played the [[Caro\u2013Kann Defence]]. Deep Blue made a knight [[sacrifice (chess)|sacrifice]] which wrecked Kasparov's defence and forced him to resign in less than twenty moves. As Kasparov later recounts, he chose to play a dubious opening in an effort to put Deep Blue out of its comfort zone. Although the knight sacrifice is a well known refutation, Kasparov reasoned that an engine wouldn't play the move without a concrete gain. The only reason Deep Blue played in that way, as was later revealed, was because that very same day of the game the creators of Deep Blue had inputted the variation into the opening database.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{block indent |1=Deep Blue vs. Kasparov <br />1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nd7 5.Ng5 Ngf6 6.Bd3 e6 7.N1f3 h6 (''diagram'') 8.Nxe6 Qe7 9.0-0 fxe6 10.Bg6+ Kd8 11.Bf4 b5 12.a4 Bb7 13.Re1 Nd5 14.Bg3 Kc8 15.axb5 cxb5 16.Qd3 Bc6 17.Bf5 exf5 18.Rxe7 Bxe7 19.c4 1\u20130}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[AlphaGo versus Lee Sedol]], similar but with Go\n* [[Arimaa]]&nbsp;\u2013 Kasparov's loss to Deep Blue inspired the creation of a new game designed to be difficult for computers, yet playable with a chess set.\n* ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]''\n* [[List of chess games]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/ | title=The official site of the matches | publisher=IBM Research | work=Deep Blue | accessdate=2007-04-17}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?pid=29912&pid2=15940 | website=[[Chessgames.com]] | title=Garry Kasparov vs Deep Blue, 12 games | accessdate=2007-04-18}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Gardner|first=Martin|authorlink=Martin Gardner\n|year=2001\n|title=A Gardner's Workout: Training the Mind and Entertaining the Spirit\n|publisher=A K Peters\n|isbn=978-1-56881-120-8\n|pages=91\u201395}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last1=Goodman|first1=David\n|last2=Keene|first2=Raymond|authorlink2=Raymond Keene\n|year=1997\n|title=Man Versus Machine: Kasparov Versus Deep Blue\n|publisher=H3\n|isbn=978-1888281064}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Hsu|first=Feng-hsiung|authorlink=Feng-hsiung Hsu\n|year=2002\n|title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the World Chess Champion\n|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]\n|isbn=0-691-09065-3\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last1=Khodarkovsky|first1=Michael\n|last2=Shamkovich|first2=Leonoid|authorlink2=Leonid Shamkovich\n|year=1997\n|title=A New Era: World Championship Chess in the Age of Deep Blue\n|publisher=Ballantine\n|isbn=978-0345408907}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=King|first=Daniel|authorlink=Daniel King (chess player)\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov v. Deeper Blue: The Ultimate Man v. Machine Challenge\n|publisher=Batsford\n|isbn=0-7134-8322-9\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Newborn|first=Monty|authorlink=Monty Newborn\n|year=1996\n|title=Kasparov versus Deep Blue: Computer Chess Comes of Age\n|publisher=Springer\n|isbn=0-387-94820-1\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book\n|last=Pandolfini|first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Pandolfini\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov and Deep Blue: The Historic Chess Match Between Man and Machine\n|publisher=Fireside Chess Library\n|isbn=9780684848525\n|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov}}\n[[Category:Chess competitions]]\n[[Category:Computer chess]]\n[[Category:Chess in the United States]]\n[[Category:1996 in chess]]\n[[Category:1997 in chess]]\n[[Category:Chess rivalries]]\n[[Category:History of chess]]\n[[Category:1996 in sports in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1997 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1996 in American sports]]\n[[Category:1997 in American sports]]\n[[Category:IBM]]\n[[Category:Human versus computer matches]]\n[[Category:1996 in computer science]]\n[[Category:1997 in computer science]]\n[[Category:Sports in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Ricklaman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGame 2 {{anchor|1997 Game 2}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deep_Blue_versus_Garry_Kasparov"}
